sperm: enterocyte of epithelium proper of small intestine
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: an enterocyte that is part of the epithelium proper of small intestine.
any goblet cell that is part of a conjunctiva.
a basal cell in the respiratory tract.
an amacrine cell with a medium dendritic field and post-synaptic terminals in s2, s3, and s4.

a cell with delicate radiating processes known as desmosomes that form intercellular bridges between other cells of this type. this cell type forms the stratum spinosum (prickle cell layer). a function of this cell is to generate keratin.

a glial cell that ensheaths multiple small diameter axons in the peripheral nervous system. the non-myelinating schwann cell is embedded among neurons (axons) with minimal extracellular spaces separating them from nerve cell membranes and has a basal lamina. cells can survive without an axon present. these cells can de-differentiate into immature schwann cells.
cd4-positive, alpha-beta t cell with the phenotype rorgamma-t-positive, cxcr3-negative, ccr6-positive, and capable of producing il-17.

sperm: smooth muscle cell of the umbilical vein
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a smooth muscle cell of the umbilical vein.

an immature erythrocyte that changes the protein composition of its plasma membrane by exosome formation and extrusion. the types of protein removed differ between species though removal of the transferrin receptor is apparent in mammals and birds.
a mesenchymal stem cell of the chorionic membrane.

sperm: type 1 vestibular sensory cell of epithelium of macula of saccule of membranous labyrinth
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a type i vestibular sensory cell that is part of the epithelium of macula of saccule of membranous labyrinth.
mature cd8 alpha-positive cd11b-negative dendritic cell is a cd8 alpha-positive cd11b-negative dendritic cell that is cd80-high, cd86-high, mhcii-high and is cd83-positive.
a fibroblast that is part of skin of back.
a slow muscle cell that contains high levels of myoglobin and oxygen storing proteins giving the cell a red appearance.

a skeletal muscle satellite cell that is mitotically quiescent. these cells are wedge shaped and have a large nuclear to cytoplasmic ratio with few organelles, a small nucleus and condensed interphase chromatin. satellite cells typically remain in this state until activated following muscle damage.

a small medullary thymic epithelial cell with a spindle shape, often arranged in groups and connected to each other by large desmosomes and interdigitations. the cytoplasm is sparse, with scanty organelles and thick bundles of cytokeratin.
a gamma-delta t cell that has an immature phenotype.
a non-terminally differentiated cell that originates from the neural crest and differentiates into a leucophore.
a langerhans cell that is in the epidermis and is cd45-positive, mhcii-positive, and cd11b-positive.
a gabaergic neuron located in the cerebral cortex that expresses vasoactive intestinal polypeptide
a leukocyte with a single non-segmented nucleus in the mature form.

sperm: central memory cd8-positive, alpha-beta t cell
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: cd8-positive, alpha-beta memory t cell with the phenotype ccr7-positive, cd127-positive, cd45ra-negative, cd45ro-positive, and cd25-negative.

sperm: endothelial cell of hepatic portal vein
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: an endothelial cell that is part of a hepatic portal vein.
a cell that takes up and metabolizes substances.

sperm: lymphatic endothelial cell of medulla ceiling
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a lymphatic endothelial cell located in the ceiling part of a lymph node medulla.
a nerve cell where transmission is mediated by nitric oxide.

the secretory neurons of the paraventricular nucleus that synthesize and secrete vasopressin, corticotropin-releasing factor (crf) and thyrotropin-releasing hormone (trh) into blood vessels in the hypothalamo-pituitary portal system.

a trophoblast cell that has a large volume of cytoplasm, is polyploid and is usually mononuclear but is also occasionally multi-nucleate. this cell type is important in establishing maternal physiology and remodeling of the vasculature of the placenta.
a f4/80-negative dendritic cell located in adipose tissue.

sperm: basophil cell of pars distalis of adenohypophysis
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a basophilic chromophil cell that of the anterior pituitary gland.
a bistratified amacrine cell with a small dendritic field that has post-synaptic terminals in s1 and the border of s1-s2, and termination of a second arbor within the border of s2-s3 and s3.
a plasmablast that secretes igm.

a group 3 innate lymphoid cell that express ror gamma t and il-7r alpha in the absence of lineage markers (e.g. cd3, cd19, b220, cd11c, gr-1), with the functional ability to interact with mesenchymal cells through lymphotoxin and tumor necrosis factor. lymphoid tissue-inducer cells are key to the development of lymph nodes and peyer s patches.
a mature alpha-beta t cell of the columnar epithelium of the gastrointestinal tract. intraepithelial t cells often have distinct developmental pathways and activation requirements.

sperm: kidney loop of henle long descending thin limb outer medulla epithelial cell
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: epithelial cell of the descending thin limb of the long loop (juxtamedullary) nephron that spans the outer medulla (inner stripe). it is known in some mammalian species that the long descending limb of the loop of henle in the outer medulla selectively expresses the secreted activin-antagonist protein follistatin (fst), the gpi-linked adhesion protein cdh13, and the protein kinase stk32a.

sperm: transitional myocyte of middle internodal tract
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a transitional myocyte that is part of the middle internodal tract.
an amacrine cell with a small, asymteric dendritic field.

sperm: mesenchymal stem cell of the bone marrow
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a mesenchymal stem cell that is part of the bone marrow.
any skin fibroblast that is part of a pedal digit skin.
female germ cell is a germ cell that supports female gamete production.
a oligopotent progenitor cell committed to the lymphoid lineage.
a pigment cell that is capable of detecting light stimulus that is involved in visual perception.
a stem cell located in the bulge of the hair follicle that can give rise to regenerate the new follicle with each hair cycle and to reepithelialize the epidermis during wound repair.
skeletogenic cell that has the potential to form an odontoblast, deposits predentine, and arises from a cranial neural crest cell.
any fibroblast that is part of a pericardium.
a double-positive thymocyte that is large (i.e. has a high forward scatter signal in flow cytometry) and is actively proliferating.

sperm: microfold cell of epithelium proper of small intestine
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a m cell that is part of the epithelium proper of small intestine.
a lineage negative, sca1-negative basophil progenitor cell that is fc epsilon rialpha-high.

sperm: endothelial cell of arteriole of lymph node
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a(n) endothelial cell that is part of a(n) arteriole of lymph node.
a renal principal cell located in the connecting tubule.
a lineage marker-negative, cd34-positive, cd38-positive, il3r-alpha-positive, il5r-alpha-positive, and cd45ra-negative eosinophil progenitor cell.
a mesenchymal stem cell of the vertebrae.
a lymphocyte of b lineage that is capable of b cell mediated immunity.

an epithelial cell of the thymus. epithelial reticular cells are pleomorphic, stellate, non-phagocytic cells which seem to be supportive in function and are held together by desmosomes. they replace the fibroblastoid reticular cells found in other lymphoid organs. other epithelial cells in the medulla have the ultrastructure of secretory cells. although different epithelial cells throughout the thymus appear alike by light microscopy their ultrastructure and function varies.

sperm: epithelial cell of esophageal cardiac gland
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: an epithelial cell of the esophageal cardiac gland that occurs both in the proximal and distal esophagus, within the lamina propia.
an adipose dendritic cell that is sirpa-positive.
a hematopoietic progenitor that has restricted self-renewal capability. cell is kit-positive, ly6-positive, cd150-negative and flt3-negative.

sperm: type i cell of adrenal cortex
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a small, polyhedral, cell found in rounded groups or curved columns with deeply staining nuclei, scanty basophilic cytoplasm and a few lipid droplets. this cell in the zona glomerulosa produces mineralocorticoids.

a double negative thymocyte that is cd3-positive, cd4-negative, cd8-negative, that that are present in the periphery in very low numbers and predominantly produce inf-gamma, tnf-alpha, and a low amount of tgf-beta, but not il-2, il-4, il-10 or il-13 upon activation.
a ciliated cell of the respiratory system. ciliated cells are present in airway epithelium.
a cuboidal epithelial cell of the kidney that regulates acid/base balance.

a cell that lines the trabecular meshwork, which is an area of tissue in the eye located around the base of the cornea, near the ciliary body, and is responsible for draining the aqueous humor from the eye via the anterior chamber (the chamber on the front of the eye covered by the cornea). this cell may play a role in regulating intraocular pressure.
ghrelin secreting cells found in the endocrine pancreas.

sperm: endothelial cell of venous sinus of red pulp of spleen
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: an endothelial cell that is part of the venous sinus of red pulp of spleen.

sperm: epithelial cell of proximal tubule segment 3
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: epithelial cell that is part of segment 3 (s3) of the proximal tubule epithelium.
fibroblast from foreskin.
a transitional myocyte that is part of the sinoatrial node.
an endothelial cell that is part of the arteriole.
a cell in vitro that is or has been maintained or propagated as part of a cell culture.
a cell whose function is determined by the generation or the reception of an electric signal.
an epithelial cell with high nuclear and cytoplasmic electron-density. this cell type is found in the deeper portions of the cortex but is more abundant in the medulla of the thymus.

a sst gabaergic cortical interneuron with a soma found in lower l2/3 and upper 5, l4 sst cells have martinotti morphology with ascending axons but denser local axons and sparser fanning-out projections to l1. l4 sst cells have smaller membrane time constant to calb2 (l2/3/5 fan martinotti cell) and non-zero afterdepolarization (adp).

sperm: small intestine peyer's patch t cell
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a t cell which resides in the peyer's patch of the small intestine.

a pluripotent stem cell has the ability to form cells from all three germ layers (ectoderm, mesoderm, and endoderm). however, unlike totipotent stem cells, they cell can not generate all the cells of the whole organism such as placenta.
a mature gamma-delta t cell that is found in the columnar epithelium of the gastrointestinal tract. these cells participate in mucosal immune responses.
a neuron that releases hypocretin as a neurotransmitter.
a neuron that uses gaba as a vesicular neurotransmitter
a cell of a hematopoietic lineage.

a nucleated immature erythrocyte, having cytoplasm generally similar to that of the earlier proerythroblast but sometimes even more basophilic, and usually regular in outline. the nucleus is still relatively large, but the chromatin strands are thicker and more deeply staining, giving a coarser appearance. the nucleoli have disappeared. this cell is cd71-positive and lacks hematopoeitic lineage markers.
a mast cell that is cd25+.
a thermoreceptor cell that detects increased temperatures.
a cell located in the synovial joint.
a smooth muscle cell that is part of any blood vessel.

a mature b cell subset originally defined as having being cd45r-positive, igm-positive, igd-positive and cd43-negative. subsequent research demonstrated being cd21-positive and cd23-negative and cd93 negative.

a respiratory stem cell found at the junction of the terminal (conductive) bronchiole and the respiratory bronchiole. this cell types gives rise to alveolar cell types and club cells in response to lung injury. this cell type expresses markers scgb1a1 and sftpc.
any dendritic cell that is part of a liver.
a natural killer cell that is developmentally immature and expresses natural killer cell receptors (nkr).
a lymphocyte of b lineage with the commitment to express an immunoglobulin complex.
a fat cell derived from a neural crest cell.
glandular cell of colon epithelium. example: goblet cells. enterocytes or absorptive cells. enteroendocrine and m cells.

sperm: transitional myocyte of atrial branch of anterior internodal tract
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a transitional myocyte that is part of the atrial branch of anterior internodal tract.
a monostratified retinal ganglion cell that has a small soma, an assymetric dendritic field with post synaptic terminals in sublaminar layer s3.
an epithelial cell derived from endoderm.
an epithelial cell found in the lining of the stomach.
an oligodendrocyte precursor cell that is committed to differentiate.
an enteroendocrine cell found in the fundus and pylorus. this cell type has dense round secretory granules that contain ghrelin.

a double-positive thymocyte that is undergoing positive selection, has high expression of the alpha-beta t cell receptor, is cd69-positive, and is in the process of down regulating the cd4 co-receptor.

a smooth muscle cell that is part of a sphincter. a sphincter is a typically circular muscle that normally maintains constriction of a natural body passage or orifice and which relaxes as required by normal physiological functioning.

an asexual 1-celled spore (primarily for perennation, not dissemination). originates endogenously and singly within part of a pre-existing cell by the contraction of the protoplast. possesses an inner secondary and often thickened hyaline or brown wall, usually impregnated with hydrophobic material.

sperm: myoepithelial cell of secondary lactiferous duct
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a myoepithelial cell that is part of the secondary lactiferous duct.

stromal cell that forms the internal covering of the vertebrate brain and produces ecm for this and the choroid plexus.
any capillary endothelial cell that is part of a placenta.
a leukocyte with abundant granules in the cytoplasm.
a cone whose sensitivity measurements have an average spectral peak of 510 nm. these cones are described in rat.

sperm: kit and sca1-positive hematopoietic stem cell
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a hematopoietic stem cell that has plasma membrane part kit-positive, sca-1-positive, cd150-positive and cd34-negative.

the principal glutaminergic neuron located in the outer third of the external plexiform layer of the olfactory bulb. a single short primary dendrite traverses the outer external plexiform layer and terminates within an olfactory glomerulus in a tuft of branches, where it receives the input from olfactory receptor neuron axon terminals. axons of the tufted cells transfer information to a number of areas in the brain, including the piriform cortex, entorhinal cortex, olfactory tubercle, and amygdala.

sperm: folliculostellate cell of pars distalis of adenohypophysis
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a supporting cell of the anterior pituitary gland involved in trophic and catabolic processes. expresses a broad spectrum of cytokeratins indicative of their epithelial nature.
a simple columnar cell that populates the entire luminal surface including the gastric pits. this cell types secrete mucus to form a thick protective, lubricant layer over the gastric wall.

sperm: epithelial cell of wall of inferior part of anal canal
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: an epithelial cell that is part of the wall of inferior part of anal canal.
a common lymphoid progenitor that is kit-low, flt3-positive, il7ralpha-positive, and sca1-low.
columnar glandular cell with irregular nucleus, copious granular endoplasmic reticulum and supranuclear granules. secretes a watery fluid containing proteins known as serous fluid.
a cell that is part of the brain vasculature.

sperm: myoepithelial cell of bronchus submucosal gland
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a(n) myoepithelial cell that is part of a(n) bronchus submucosal gland.
a plasmacytoid dendritic cell with the phenotype hla-dra-positive, cd123-positive, and cd11c-negative.

a late neutrophilic metamyelocyte in which the nucleus is indented to more than half the distance to the farthest nuclear margin but in no area being condensed to a single filament. the nucleus is in the form of a curved or coiled band, not having acquired the typical multilobar shape of the mature neutrophil. these cells are fmlp receptor-positive, cd11b-positive, cd35-negative, and cd49d-negative.
immature interstitial dendritic cell is a interstitial dendritic cell that is cd80-low, cd86-low, and mhcii-low.

an erythroid progenitor cell that is cd34-positive and is glya-negative.

a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a b220-low cd38-negative unswitched memory b cell is a cd38-negative unswitched memory b cell that has the phenotype b220-low, cd38-negative, igd-positive, cd138-negative, and igg-negative.

sperm: nonkeratinized epithelial cell of inferior part of anal canal
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a nonkeratinized cell epithleial cell of the inferior part of the anal canal.
a slow muscle cell that has large amounts of myoglobin, stores energy as triglycerides, generates atp by the oxidative method and is resistant to fatigue.

sperm: basal cell of epithelium of trachea
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a basal cell that is part of the epithelium of trachea.
a cuboidal epithelial cell of the kidney which secretes acid and reabsorbs base to regulate acid/base balance.
an ilc1 cell in the human with the phenotype cd56-negative, il-7ralpha-positive, t-bet-positive.

a polarized columnar cell that covesr the lateral surface of the cochlear duct, secretes potassium ions and forms a continuous sheet in contact with the endolymph. marginal cells form extensive interdigitations with the basal and intermediate cells in the normal adult stria.
an undifferentiated fibroblast that can be stimulated to form a fat cell.
any goblet cell that is part of the tracheobronchial epithelium.

sperm: cd27-high, cd11b-high natural killer cell, mouse
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a mature natural killer cell that is cd27-high and cd11b-high. this cell type is capable of interferon-gamma secretion.
a specialized hair cell that has an elongated kinocilium upon which an otolith accretes. the tether cell then anchors the otolith in place.

bottle-shaped with narrow neck. broad, rounded basal portion where nucleus is located. stereocilia and a single kinocilium is present apically. receive nerve bouton at their base from an afferent cup-shaped (chalice or calyx) nerve ending.
any fibroblast that is part of a periodontal ligament.
a medium spiny neuron that expresses dopamine type 1 receptors and projects to the globus pallidus internus or the substantia nigra pars reticulata.

a hematopoietic stem cell that resides in the fetal liver. in mice, this cell type is first observed at e10.5. this cell type is mhc-positive, hsa-positive, aa4.1-positive, cd45-positive, sca-1 positive, cd150-positive, cd48-negative and cd244-negative.
a cell whose function is determined by its response to an electric signal.

a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a dermal dendritic cell isolated from skin draining lymph nodes that is langerin-negative, mhc-ii-positive, and cd4-negative and cd8a-negative.
a mucosa-associated lymphoid tissue macrophage found in the mucosa-associated lymphoid tissues of the gut.

one of the two photoreceptor cell types of the vertebrate retina. in rods the photopigment is in stacks of membranous disks separate from the outer cell membrane. rods are more sensitive to light than cones, but rod mediated vision has less spatial and temporal resolution than cone vision.
a mesothelial cell that has undergone mesothelial-to-mesenchymal transition (mmt) to become a fibroblast cell.

a eosinophil precursor in the granulocytic series, being a cell intermediate in development between a promyelocyte and a metamyelocyte.in this stage, production of primary granules is complete and eosinophil-specific granules has started. no nucleolus is present. these cells are integrin alpha-m-positive, cd13-positive, cd15-positive, cd16-negative, cd24-positive, and cd33-positive.
a cell with more than one nucleus.
characteristic early embryonic cell with a bottle or flask shape that is first to migrate inwards at the blastopore during gastrulation in amphibians.
an adipose macrophage that does not express f4/80but is mhc-ii-positive. this cell type exhibits autofluorescence under typical flow cyometry conditions.

a rapidly cycling mature b cell that has distinct phenotypic characteristics and is involved in t-dependent immune responses and located typically in the germinal centers of lymph nodes. this cell type expresses ly77 after activation.
a motor neuron that is capable of directly inhibiting muscle contraction.
chondrocyte that is terminally differentiated, produces type x collagen, is large in size, and often associated with the replacement of cartilage by bone (endochondral ossification).
a mono-stratified retinal ganglion cell that has a large dendritic field, a medium dendritic arbor, and a long secondary dendrite shaft with post synaptic terminals in sublaminar layer s4.

a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a type i nk t cell that has been recently activated, secretes interferon-gamma and il-4, and has the phenotype cd4-positive, cd69-positive, and downregulated nk markers.
cd11c-negative plasmacytoid dendritic cell is a leukocyte is cd11c-negative, cd45ra-positive, cd85g-positive(ilt7), cd123-positive, cd303-positive.
any cell capable of ingesting particulate matter via phagocytosis.

sperm: l2/3/5 fan martinotti sst gabaergic cortical interneuron (mmus)
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a sst gabaergic cortical interneuron that has "fanning-out' martinotti morphology that is found in layer 2/3/5 of the cerebral cortex. they have local axon arbor and long ascending axons that spreads horizontally and arborizes significantly in l1.

a large epithelial cell with an extremely acidophilic and granular cytoplasm, containing vast numbers of mitochondria. such cells may undergo neoplastic transformation. from the greek word onkos meaning swelling, this cell type is found in parathyroid, salivary and thyroid glands.
a neuron that has its soma located in ca1-3 of the hippocampus.
a fibroblast of the lymphatic system.

sperm: external supporting cell of vestibular epithelium
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: an auditory epithelial support cell located in the vestibular epithelium that has many hallmarks of glial cells. this cell type express glial markers such as vimentin, s100, glutamate-aspartate transporter, low affinity neurotrophin receptor p75, glial fibrillary acidic protein, and proteolipid protein.
a cd4-positive, alpha-beta t cell with the phenotype ccr7-negative, cd45ra-positive.
a progenitor cell with hepatic and biliary lineage potential, identified in mouse and human, and anatomically restricted to the ductal plate of fetal liver.

sperm: transitional myocyte of left branch of atrioventricular bundle
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a transitional myocyte that is part of the left branch of atrioventricular bundle.
a t cell that is located in the intestinal epithelium and is capable of a mucosal immune response.
an alpha-beta t cell that has an immature phenotype and has not completed t cell selection.
a cd4-positive, alpha-beta t cell that has cytotoxic function.

a eosinophil precursor in the granulocytic series, being a cell intermediate in development between a myelocyte and a band form cell. the nucleus becomes indented where the indentation is smaller than half the distance to the farthest nuclear margin. chromatin becomes coarse and clumped. specific granules predominate while primary granules are rare.
a cd38-positive igg memory b cell is a class switched memory b cell that expresses igg on the cell surface with the phenotype cd38-positive and igg-positive.
any hematopoietic cell that is a precursor of some other hematopoietic cell type.
any cell in the midgut (middle subdivision of a digestive tract) of an insect larva.
an epithelial supporting cell located in the cochlea.
a cell that specializes in controlled release of one or more substances.

sperm: cd4-negative, cd8-negative type i nk t cell
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a type i nk t cell that has the phenotype cd4-negative and cd8-negative.
a t cell expressing an alpha-beta t cell receptor and the cd8 coreceptor.
a cell found in the embryo before the formation of all the gem layers is complete.
any microvascular endothelial cell that is part of a breast.

sperm: kidney loop of henle long descending thin limb inner medulla epithelial cell
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: epithelial cell of the descending thin limb of the long loop (juxtamedullary) nephron that spans the inner medulla. it is known in some mammalian species that the long descending limb of the loop of henle in the inner medulla selectively expresses the nuclear receptor nr2e3, the ig kappa chain igkc, and the secreted protein dermokine (dmkn). slc14a2, which expresses a urea transporter, is also expressed in the inner medulla.
any skin fibroblast that is part of a arm.
a macrophage located in adipose tissue that is cd45-positive, cd11c-positive, and sirpa-positive.
a neuron that release noradrenaline (noriphinephrine) as a neurotransmitter.
a trophoblast of placental villi. these cells fuse to form synctial trophoplast - the placental side of the interface between the placenta and maternal blood sinusoids in the decidua.

sperm: neuron of the ventral spinal cord
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a neuron of the ventral spinal cord.

sperm: brush cell of epithelium proper of large intestine
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: brush cell found in the epithelial layer of the colon.
a cardiac myocyte that is connected to other cardiac myocytes by transverse intercalated discs (go:0014704) at a regular interval.
a spermatid in an early stage of maturation that has a round morphology and is transcriptionally active.
a motor neuron that innervates both intrafusal and extrafusal muscle fibers. low abundancy. they control both muscle contraction and responsiveness of the sensory feedback from muscle spindles.
a glandular cell found in the epithelium of the small intestine. example: enterocytes, goblet cells, enteroendocrine cells. paneth cells. m cells. somatostatin-secreting cells (d-cells) .

this cell type produces and secretes melatonin and forms the pineal parenchyma. extending from each cell body, which has a spherical, oval or lobulated mucleus, are one or more tortuous basophilic processes, containing parallel microtubules known as synaptic ribbons. these processes end in expanded terminal buds near capillaries or less, frequently, ependymal cells of the pineal recess. the terminal buds contain granular endoplasmic reticulum, mitochondria and electron-dense cored vesicles, which store monoamines and polypeptide hormones, release of which appears to require sympathetic innervation.

a b cell of distinct lineage and surface marker expression. b-1 b cells are thought to be the primary source of natural igm immunoglobulin, that is, igm produced in large quantities without prior antigenic stimulation and generally reactive against various microorganisms, as well as the source of t-independent iga immunoglobulin in the mucosal areas. these cells are cd43-positive.
a retinal ganglion cell b that has a very small but very dense dendritic field, and has post synaptic terminals in s2.

a hillock cell that is located in respiratory epithelium. in some mammalian species, this cell type has been noted to express krt13 and krt4 and is postulated to play a role in squamous barrier function and immunomodulation.
a non-striated, elongated, spindle-shaped cell found lining the digestive tract, uterus, and blood vessels. they develop from specialized myoblasts (smooth muscle myoblast).
a transit amplifying cell that is part of a crypt of lieberkuhn of large intestine.
any fibroblast that is part of a cardiac atrium.
any keratinocyte that is part of a hair follicle.

a cell from the outer syncytial layer of the trophoblast of an early mammalian embryo, directly associated with the maternal blood supply. it secretes hcg in order to maintain progesterone secretion and sustain a pregnancy.
a steroid hormone secreting cell that secretes estradiol.
a hillock cell that is part of the urethra.
a cd8-positive, alpha-beta positive t cell expressing gata-3 and secreting il-4.

sperm: external epithelial cell of tympanic membrane
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: epithelial cell found on the external side of the tympanic membrane
a thymocyte that has the phenotype cd4-negative, cd8-negative, cd44-positive, and cd25-positive.
a diploid cell that has derived from a spermatogonium and can subsequently begin meiosis and divide into two haploid secondary spermatocytes.
a circulating gamma-delta t cell that expresses rorgamma(t), is cd27-negative and is capable of il-17 secretion.

sperm: keratinized cell of the oral mucosa
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a keratinized cell located in the hard palate or gingiva.

sperm: fibroblast of the reticular layer of dermis
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: any fibroblast that is part of a reticular layer of dermis.
heterochromatin that is arranged in a carthwheel pattern.

sperm: endothelial cell of periportal hepatic sinusoid
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: an endothelial cell found in the periportal region hepatic sinusoid, near the portal triad. the fenestrae of these cells are larger but fewer in number compared with those of endothelial cells near the centrilobular region of the hepatic sinusoid.
an olfactory receptor cell in which the apical ending of the dendrite is a knob that bears numerous microvilli.

a myeloid dendritic cell found in the blood, lymph nodes, tonsil, bone marrow, and spleen that is cd141-positive (bdca-3), xcr1-positive, and clec9a-positive. this cell-type can cross-present antigen to cd8-positive t cells and can produce inteferon-beta.
glial cell of cerebral cortex.
an alpha-beta t cell that is found in the lamina propria of mucosal tissues and is restricted by the mr-1 molecule.
a cell found predominately in the blood.
a phagocyte from organisms in the nematoda or protostomia clades.
a neuroglial cell of ectodermal origin, i.e., the astrocytes and oligodendrocytes considered together.

a splenic macrophage found in the marginal zone of the spleen, involved in recognition and clearance of particulate material from the splenic circulation. markers include f4/80-negative, marco-positive, sr-a-positive, sign-r1-positive, and dectin2-positive.
notochordal cell that is inner portion of the notochord and becomes vacuolated as development proceeds.
an igg memory b cell is a class switched memory b cell that is class switched and expresses igg on the cell surface.
a fat-storing cell found mostly in the abdominal cavity and subcutaneous tissue of mammals. fat is usually stored in the form of triglycerides.

a precursor cell that has a tendency to differentiate into a specific type of cell. they are descendants of stem cells, only they are more constrained in their differentiation potential or capacity for self-renewal, and are often more limited in both senses.
neuron of the cerebellum.
specialized cardiac myocyte which is in the internodal tract and atrioventricular node. the cell is more slender than ordinary atrial myocytes and has more myofibrils than nodal myocytes.
immature cd11c-low plasmacytoid dendritic cell is a cd11c-low plasmacytoid dendritic cell that is cd80-low and cd86-low.
a neuron that uses acetylcholine as a vesicular neurotransmitter.

a type ec enteroendocrine cell in the duodenum and jejunum that stores and secretes motilin and 5-hydroxytryptamine.
a tissue macrophage that is in the pleural space.
a cell that is part of a cardiac valve.

a retinal ganglion a cell found in the retina with large somata, often polygonal in shape. the dendritic fields consist of three to seven stout dendrites that are sparce near soma. dendrites terminate in s4.
a peptide hormone secreting cell pituitary that produces luteinizing hormone.

sperm: dentate gyrus of hippocampal formation granule cell
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: the principal cell type of the dentate gyrus.
a neuroglial cell of the peripheral nervous system which forms the insulating myelin sheaths of peripheral axons.
a myoepithelial cell that is part of the lactiferous duct.
a leukocyte with a single non-segmented nucleus in the mature form found in the circulatory pool of blood.
a progenitor cell restricted to the lymphoid lineage.
a type of mouse mesothelial fibroblast that is derived from the neural crest, is localized on blood vessels, and is a key component of the pia and arachnoid membranes surrounding the brain.

sperm: cd25-positive, cd27-positive immature gamma-delta t cell
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a cd25-positive, cd27-positive immature gamma-delta t cell found in the thymus that has an immature phenotype (i.e. cd24-high, cd25-high, cd62l-high, cd44-high, cd2-low, cd5-low).
a pigment cell is a cell that contains pigment granules.

sperm: mucous neck cell of gastric gland
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a neck cell that secretes mucus within the stomach. its products are distinct histochemically from those of the surface mucous cells of stomach.

sperm: microfold cell of epithelium of intestinal villus
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a m cell that is part of the epithelium of intestinal villus.
a spiral ganglion neuron that innervates outer hair cells. type 1 spiral ganglion neurons are unmyelinated and unipolar.
a cell involved in the formation of a monocyte (monopoiesis).
the set of neurons that receives neural inputs via bipolar, horizontal and amacrine cells. the axons of these cells make up the optic nerve.

a mechanoreceptor in the organ of corti. in mammals the outer hair cells are arranged in three rows which are further from the modiolus than the single row of inner hair cells. the motile properties of the outer hair cells may contribute actively to tuning the sensitivity and frequency selectivity of the cochlea.
the basic cellular unit of nervous tissue. each neuron consists of a body, an axon, and dendrites. their purpose is to receive, conduct, and transmit impulses in the nervous system.
any cardiac muscle cell that is part of a cardiac ventricle.

a cd38-positive naive b cell is a mature b cell that has the phenotype cd38-positive, surface igd-positive, surface igm-positive, and cd27-negative, and that has not yet been activated by antigen in the periphery.
a neuron that is part of a peripheral nervous system.
an amicrine that stratifies dendrites at two and only two locations.
a motor neuron that is generated only on limb levels and send axons into the limb mesenchyme.
a fibroblast located in the thymic capsule.
a goblet cell that is located in the anorectum.
undifferentiated. mitotic stem cell for other epithelial cell types. rounded or elliptical with little cytoplasm and few organelles. contain cytokeratin intermediate filament.

an undifferentiated neural cell that originates from the neuroectoderm and has the capacity both to perpetually self-renew without differentiating and to generate multiple central nervous system neuronal and glial cell types.
cd4-positive alpha-beta t cell with the phenotype foxp3-positive, cd25-positive, cd62l-positive, and ctla-4 positive with regulatory function.
a cell that is maintained or propagated in a controlled artificial environment for use in an investigation.
a specialized mononuclear osteoclast associated with the absorption and removal of bone, precursor of multinuclear osteoclasts.
a lymphatic endothelial cell located in a lymph node trabecula.
a cell with both myofibrils and secretory granules.
a myeloid suppressor cell that is gr1-low and cd11c-positive.
any basket cell that is part of a ammon's horn.
neuron with two neurites that are fused grossly when they protrude from the soma and bifurcate a short distance from the soma.
a thymocyte expressing the alpha-beta t cell receptor complex as well as both the cd4 and cd8 coreceptors.

a modified epidermal cell located in the stratum basale. they are found mostly in areas where sensory perception is acute. merkel cells are closely associated with an expanded terminal bulb of an afferent myelinated nerve fiber.
an immature cd1a-positive dermal dendritic cell is cd80-low, cd86-low, and mhcii-low.
a smooth muscle cell of the trachea.

a bulbous cell that is medially placed in one row in the organ of corti. in contrast to the outer hair cells, the inner hair cells are fewer in number, have fewer sensory hairs, and are less differentiated.
neuron of lateral ventricle.
the various hormone- or neurotransmitter-secreting cells present throughout the mucosa of the stomach.
a pp cell located in the islets of the pancreas.

sperm: dark chief cell of parathyroid gland
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a chief cell that is smaller than light chief cells and has a smaller and darker nucleus and a finely granular cytoplasm with many granules.
an epithelial cell of the uterus.
neuron found in the spiral ganglion.
a pp cell found in intestine.

sperm: epithelial cell of early distal convoluted tubule
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: an epithelial cell located in the early distal convoluted tubule.
a tissue-resident macrophage located in the bone marrow. this cell type is b220-negative, cd3e-negative, ly-6c-negative, cd115-positive, f4/80-positive.

a cell lining the outside of the blastocyst. after binding to the endometrium, trophoblast cells develop into two distinct layers, an inner layer of mononuclear cytotrophoblast cells and an outer layer of continuous multinuclear cytoplasm, the syncytiotrophoblast cells, which form the early fetal-maternal interface.
granule cell that is part of the olfactory bulb.

sperm: lymph node mantle zone b cell
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a b lymphocyte that resides in the mantle zone of the lymph node germinal center. these are generally igm and igd positive activated b cells that form a 'corona' around the germinal center and are part of the establishment of a secondary lymphatic follicule.
a g11 retinal ganglion cell that has post synaptic terminals in sublaminar layer s2 and is depolarized by decreased illumination of their receptive field center

a supporting cell for the developing female gamete in the ovary of mammals. they develop from the coelomic epithelial cells of the gonadal ridge. granulosa cells form a single layer around the mammalian oocyte in the primordial ovarian follicle and advance to form a multilayered cumulus oophorus surrounding the ovum in the graafian follicle. the major functions of granulosa cells include the production of steroids and lh receptors.
a non-terminally differentiated cell that originates from the neural crest and differentiates into a cyanophore.
an epithelial cell of the esophagus.

a transitional stage b cell that migrates from the bone marrow into the peripheral circulation, and finally to the spleen. this cell type has the phenotype surface igm-positive, surface igd-negative, cd21-negative, cd23-negative, and cd62l-negative, and cd93-positive. this cell type has also been described as igm-high, cd19-positive, b220-positive, aa4-positive, and cd23-negative.
a nk1.1-positive t cell that is nkga2-positive.
an endothelial cell found in the mucosa associated with the facial skeleton.
a stromal cell of the endometrium that is fibroblastic in appearance. during decidualization this cell may differentiate into a decidual stromal cell.
a megakaryocyte progenitor cell that is cd34-negative, cd41-positive and cd42-positive.
an m9 retinal ganglion cells with synaptic terminals in s2 and is depolarized by illumination of its receptive field center.

sperm: endothelial cell of venule of lymph node
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a(n) endothelial cell that is part of a(n) venule of lymph node.
a ciliated cell of the endometrial luminal epithelium.
a group 2 innate lymphoid cell in the human with the phenotype cd25-positive, cd127-positive, cd161-positive, and gata-3-positive.

sperm: fibroblast of connective tissue of nonglandular part of prostate
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a fibroblast that is part of the connective tissue of nonglandular part of prostate.
an endothelial cell that lines any of the venous cavities through which blood passes in various glands and organs such as the spleen and liver.
a macroconidium that has only one nucleus.
a secondary lymphoid organ macrophage found in the spleen.

sperm: gastrointestinal tract (lamina propria) macrophage of large intestine
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a macrophage which is resident in the lamina propria of the large intestine.
a pigment cell derived from the neural crest. contains pteridine and/or carotenoid pigments in structures called pterinosomes or erythrosomes. this gives an orange to red appearance.
a smooth muscle cell that is part of the jejunum.

mast cell subtype that contains only the serine protease trypase in its granules. these cells are primarily found in mucosal tissue, such as intestinal mucosa and alveoli. they depend upon t-cells for development of phenotype.
an immature astrocyte.

sperm: serous cell of epithelium of terminal bronchiole
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a serous secreting cell that is part of the epithelium of terminal bronchiole.

a cell that is found in a zone occupying the bottom region of the crypt. provide the source of most of the cell types of the intestinal epithelium. proliferate by mitotic division. differentiates into columnar or goblet cells.

a double negative post-natal thymocyte that has a t cell receptor consisting of a gamma chain containing a vgamma2 segment, and a delta chain. this cell type is cd4-negative, cd8-negative and cd24-positive.

a mononuclear phagocyte present in variety of tissues, typically differentiated from monocytes, capable of phagocytosing a variety of extracellular particulate material, including immune complexes, microorganisms, and dead cells.
a taste receptor cell that has a short microvilli, a projecting apical region, a large rounded nucleus, and expresses taste chemoreceptors thus making them the transducing cell for taste qualities.

sperm: immature nk t cell stage i
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a cd24-high, cd4-low, cd8-low, cd44-negative, nk1.1-negative nk t cell.
a brush cell found in the epithelium of lobular bronchiole.
any chondrocyte that is part of the tracheobronchial tree.
a promyelocyte committed to the basophil lineage.

a terminally differentiated, post-mitotic, antibody secreting cell of the b cell lineage with the phenotype cd138-positive, surface immunonoglobulin-negative, and mhc class ii-negative. plasma cells are oval or round with extensive rough endoplasmic reticulum, a well-developed golgi apparatus, and a round nucleus having a characteristic cartwheel heterochromatin pattern and are devoted to producing large amounts of immunoglobulin.

sperm: smooth muscle cell of the brachiocephalic vasculature
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a smooth muscle cell of the bachiocephalic vasculature.

sperm: type ii cell of adrenal cortex
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a cell in the zona fasciculata that produce glucocorticoids, e.g cortisol.

sperm: endo-epithelial cell of pharyngotympanic part of viscerocranial mucosa
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: an endocranial viscerocranial mucosa cell that is part of viscerocranial mucosa.
a lin-negative, mhc-ii-negative, cd11c-positive, flt3-positive cell with intermediate expression of sirp-alpha.

a neuron of the human embryonic marginal zone which display, as a salient feature, radial ascending processes that contact the pial surface, and a horizontal axon plexus located in the deep marginal zone. one feature of these cells in mammals is that they express the reelin gene.
a cell involved in the elimination of metabolic and foreign toxins, and in maintaining the ionic, acid-base and water balance of biological fluids.
a trophoblast cell that arises in the junctional zone (basal plate) of the placenta.
a cell that is usually basal in position, cuboidal with round nucleus, short microvilli, secretes pepsinogen.
a thymic macrophage found in the thymic cortex.
parasympathetic neurons are part of the parasympathetic nervous sysem and the cell bodies lie in the brain and sacral region of the spinal cord. the neurons are mainly cholinergic.

sperm: growth hormone releasing hormone secreting cell
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a peptide hormone secreting cell that secretes growth hormone releasing hormone.
a goblet cell that is located in the colon.

sperm: clear chief cell of parathyroid gland
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a chief cell of parathyroid glands that does not stain with hematoxylin or eosin. this cell is larger, has a larger nucleus and fewer secretory granules than dark chief cells.
any blood vessel endothelial cell that is part of a microvascular endothelium.
a macrophage located in the vermiform appendix.

a cell that stores epinephrine secretory vesicles. during times of stress, the nervous system signals the vesicles to secrete their hormonal content. their name derives from their ability to stain a brownish color with chromic salts. characteristically, they are located in the adrenal medulla and paraganglia of the sympathetic nervous system.

sperm: urothelial cell of trigone of urinary bladder
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: an urothelial cell that is part of the trigone of urinary bladder.
a mesenchymal stem cell of liver.
a thymocyte that lacks expression of cd4 and cd8.
a gut-associated lymphoid tissue macrophage found in lamina propria of the gut.
a specialized epithelial secretory cell that moves chloride ions and water across the tubule epithelium.
a thymic medullary epithelial cell considered to be a pre-aire mtec population.
a cell type found in the spherical or ovoid clusters of receptor cells found mainly in the epithelium of the tongue and constituting the end organs of the sense of taste.
a pericyte cell located in the kidney interstitium.
a cd8-positive, cd4-negative thymocyte that is cd24-positive and expresses high levels of the alpha-beta t cell receptor.

a class switched memory b cell is a memory b cell that has undergone ig class switching and therefore is igm-negative on the cell surface. these cells are cd27-positive and have either igg, ige, or iga on the cell surface.
a fibroblast-like cell that provides support at neuromuscular junctions in vertebrates and are localized outside the synaptic basal lamina.
immature cd8 alpha-low langerhans cell is a cd8 alpha-low langerhans cell that is cd80-low, cd86-low, and mhcii-low.
skeletogenic cell that has the potential to develop into a cementoblast.
any osteoblast that is part of a skull.
a mucous cell in the epithelium of the stomach.
a smooth muscle cell of the myometrium that enlarges and stretches during pregnancy, and contracts in response to oxytocin.
an endothelial cell that is part of some peritubular capillary.
a somatic cell located in skeletal muscle.

an epithelial cell that is part of the fallopian tube epithelium that secretes mucous fluid and oviduct-specific products through the stimulation of estrogen and luteinizing hormone. the fallopian tube secretory cell has approximately the same height as the ciliated cell and is usually a more narrow columnar cell. the nucleus is ovoid and perpendicular to the long axis of the cell. the chromatin is more dense and the nucleolus smaller than that seen in the ciliated cell.

sperm: marginal zone b cell of spleen
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a mature b cell that is located in the marginal zone of the spleen with the phenotype cd23-negative and cd21-positive and expressing a b cell receptor usually reactive to bacterial cell wall components or senescent self components such as oxidized-ldl. this cell type is also described as being cd19-positive, b220-positive, igm-high, aa4-negative, cd35-high.
immature cd8 alpha-positive cd11b-negative dendritic cell is a cd8 alpha-positive cd11b-negative dendritic cell that is cd80-low, cd86-low, and mhcii-low.
a mesothelial cell that is part of the visceral peritoneum.
a nucleus size quality which is relatively high compared to the amount of cytoplasm present in the same cell.
a central nervous system neuron that stratifies at one and only one location.
a specialized fibroblast found in the medulla of lymph node.
an oncocyte located in the thyroid.
transit-amplifying cells (tacs) are an undifferentiated population in transition between stem cells and differentiated cells.
an epithelial cell of the large intestine.

a melanocyte located between the epithelial marginal cell layer and the mesodermal basal cell layer within the intrastrial space. the predominant cellular component of the electrogenic machinery that generates an endocochlear potential (80-100 mv) .

an epithelial ciliated cell that is part of the fallopian tube. this cell type is found mainly on the apex of the mucosal folds and contributes, together with peristaltic contractions, to the self-propulsion of spermatozoa, the transport of ovum during ovulation and the transport of the fertilized ovum to the intramural fallopian tube. a fallopian tube ciliated cell has a columnar shape and contains an oval or round nucleus, often located perpendicular or parallel to the long axis of the cell.
a neuron of the raphe nuclei.
a cell that, by division or terminal differentiation, can give rise to other cell types.
a tissue-resident macrophage of the renal glomerular mesangium involved in the disposal and degradation of filtration residues, presentation of antigen to t cells and in tissue remodeling.

sperm: immature nk t cell stage iii
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a cd24-low, cd44-positive, dx5-low, nk1.1-negative nk t cell.
a male germ cell that develops from spermatogonia. the euploid primary spermatocytes undergo meiosis and give rise to the haploid secondary spermatocytes which in turn give rise to spermatids.
a cell that is part of some vasa recta ascending limb.

sperm: stromal cell of lamina propria of large intestine
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a stromal cell found in the lamina propria of the large intestine.

sperm: cd8-positive, cd28-negative, alpha-beta regulatory t cell
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: cd8-positive, alpha-beta positive regulatory t cell with the phenotype cd28-negative and foxp3-positive.
a neuron with soma location in the reticular formation with axons that extend into the spinal cord such. reticulospinal neuron activity can lead to a variety of motor behaviors.
a conventional dendritic cell that expresses cd11b (itgam).
cell that provides some or all mechanical, nutritional and phagocytic support to their neighbors.

a neuron found in the anterior part of the ventral cochlear nucleus that has the appearance of bushes, having short dendrites. bushy cells give outputs to different parts of the superior olivary complex.
a alpha-beta intraepithelial t cell found in the columnar epithelium of the gastrointestinal tract. intraepithelial t cells often have distinct developmental pathways and activation requirements.
a retinal ganglion a2 cell with dendrites terminating in s4.
a retinal ganglion cell c outer that has a medium dendritic field and a dense dendritic arbor.

sperm: cd4-positive, cd25-positive, ccr4-positive, alpha-beta regulatory t cell
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a cd4-positive, cd25-positive, alpha-beta regulatory t cell with the additional phenotype ccr4-positive.
an epithelial cell of the proximal tubule of the kidney.
a skeletal muscle satellite cell that undergoes symmetric division to produce two adult skeleltal muscle myoblasts.
mature cd8 alpha-low langerhans cell is a cd8 alpha-low langerhans cell that that is cd80-high, cd86-high, mhcii-high and is cd83-positive.
an innate lymphoid cell in the human with the phenotype klrg1-positive that is a precusor for ilc2 cells.

sperm: luminal cell of acinus of lactiferous gland
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a luminal epithelial cell of mammary gland located in acinus of structure.
cd7-negative lymphoid progenitor cell is a lymphoid progenitor cell that is cd34-positive, cd7-negative and cd45ra-negative.
an epithelial cell of the parathyroid gland.

a rounded or elliptical epithelial cell, with pale-staining open face nucleus and pale cytoplasm rich in free ribosomes and clusters of centrioles. form a distinct basal zone spaced slightly from the basal surface of the epithelium.
a macroconidium that has more than one nucleus.
an innate lymphoid cell that is capable of producing t-helper 2-cell associated cytokines upon stimulation.
an epithelial cell that is part of the lacrimal sac.
an efferent neuron that passes from the central nervous system or a ganglion toward or to a muscle and conducts an impulse that causes or inhibits movement.
a lymphocyte of b lineage that is devoted to secreting large amounts of immunoglobulin.

a tissue-resident macrophage found in the alveoli of the lungs. ingests small inhaled particles resulting in degradation and presentation of the antigen to immunocompetent cells. markers include f4/80-positive, cd11b-/low, cd11c-positive, cd68-positive, sialoadhesin-positive, dectin-1-positive, mr-positive, cx3cr1-negative.

sperm: smooth muscle cell of large intestine smooth muscle circular layer
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a(n) smooth muscle cell that is part of a(n) large intestine smooth muscle circular layer.
an epithelial cell of the exocrine pancreas.
a stem cell that can give rise to multiple lineages of cells.
a class of large neuroglial (macroglial) cells in the central nervous system. form the insulating myelin sheath of axons in the central nervous system.
a specialized epithelial cell that is capable of synthesizing and secreting certain biomolecules.
an asexual, nonmotile spore formed by higher fungi. conidia are usually made from the side or tip of specialized sporogenous cells and do not form by progressive cleavage of the cytoplasm.

sperm: basal cell of epithelium of respiratory bronchiole
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a basal cell that is part of the epithelium of respiratory bronchiole.

an epithelial, transitional cell type between basal and secretory. located in stratified, non-ciliated structures (called hillocks) with high cell turnover in epithelium. in some mammalian species, this cell type has been noted to express krt13 and is postulated to play a role in squamous barrier function and immunomodulation.

skeletogenic cell that has the potential to develop into an ameloblast. located in the inner enamel epithelium, these cells elongate, their nuclei shift distally (away from the dental papilla), and their cytoplasm becomes filled with organelles needed for synthesis and secretion of enamel proteins.
a progenitor cell committed to the megakaryocyte and erythroid lineages.
an interrenal chromaffin cell found in teleosts that contain small, homogeneous electron-lucent granules that are separated from the vesicular membrane by a visible halo.
a stromal cell of the prostate.
diploid cell produced by the fusion of sperm cell nucleus and egg cell.

the small neuron in the glomerular layer of the olfactory bulb whose dendrites arborize within a glomerulus, where it receives synaptic input from olfactory receptor cell axon terminals, and also engages in dendrodendritic interactions with mitral and tufted cell dendrites. uses both gaba and dopamine as a neurotransmitter.

sperm: cd56-positive, cd161-positive immature natural killer cell, human
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a natural killer cell that is developmentally immature, has the phenotype cd34-negative, cd56-positive, cd117-positive, cd122-positive,and cd161-positive.
a sperm bearing a y chromosome. chromosomal and genetic sex is established at fertilization in mammals and depends upon whether an x-bearing sperm or a y-bearing sperm fertilizes the x-bearing ovum.
a basophilic erythroblast that is lyg 76-high and is kit-negative.

sperm: paneth cell of epithelium of crypt of lieberkuhn of small intestine
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a paneth cell that is part of the epithelium of crypt of lieberkuhn of small intestine.

a rapidly proliferating population of cells that differentiate from stem cells of the intestinal crypt of the colon. stem cells located in the crypts of lieberk hn give rise to proliferating progenitor or transit amplifying cells that differentiate into the four major epithelial cell types. these include columnar absorptive cells or enterocytes, mucous secreting goblet cells, enteroendocrine cells and paneth cells.
a progesterone secreting cell in the corpus luteum that develops from theca cells.

a cell that is found in almost all tissues containing numerous basophilic granules and capable of releasing large amounts of histamine and heparin upon activation. progenitors leave bone marrow and mature in connective and mucosal tissue. mature mast cells are found in all tissues, except the bloodstream. their phenotype is cd117-high, cd123-negative, cd193-positive, cd200r3-positive, and fceri-high. stem-cell factor (kit-ligand. scf) is the main controlling signal of their survival and development.

sperm: l5 intratelencephalic projecting glutamatergic neuron of the primary motor cortex
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: an intratelencephalic-projecting glutamatergic neuron with a soma found in l5 of the primary motor cortex.

sperm: type 2 vestibular sensory cell of epithelium of macula of saccule of membranous labyrinth
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a type ii vestibular sensory cell that is part of the epithelium of macula of saccule of membranous labyrinth.

a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a progenitor cell with the potential to differentiate into luminal epithelial cells of mammary glands. in mouse, cd61 and c-kit were found to be coexpressed by the majority of, but not all, committed luminal progenitor cells.
a smooth muscle cell of the aorta.
a bistratifed retinal ganglion cell that has small, symmetric dendritic fields that terminate in s2 and s4.

sperm: cd8-positive, alpha-beta memory t cell, cd45ro-positive
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a cd8-positive, alpha-beta t cell with memory phenotype indicated by being cd45ro and cd127-positive. this cell type is also described as being cd25-negative, cd44-high, and cd122-high.

a cell located in the outermost proliferative zone of the external germinal layer that can differentiate into astroglial cells and granule cells. this cell type is glial fibrillary acidic protein-positive and nk1-positive.

skeletogenic cell that secretes osteoid, is capable of producing mineralized (hydroxyapatite) matrix, is located adjacent to or within osteoid tissue, and arises from the transformation of a preosteoblast cell.
a gut-associated lymphoid tissue macrophage found in the peyer's patches.
muscle cell which has as its direct parts myofilaments organized into sarcomeres.
a precursor in the monocytic series, being a cell intermediate in development between the monoblast and monocyte. this cell is cd11b-positive and has fine azurophil granules.
a fungal cell with two genetically distinct haploid nuclei.

sperm: stromal cell of anorectum lamina propria
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a stromal cell found in the lamina propria of the anorectum.
an epithelial cell of the cervix.
a cell located between the pinealocytes.

a fully differentiated eosinophil, a granular leukocyte with a nucleus that usually has two lobes connected by one or more slender threads, and cytoplasm containing coarse, round granules that are uniform in size and which can be stained by the dye eosin. cells are also differentiated from other granulocytes by a small nuclear-to-cytoplasm ratio (1:3). this cell type is cd49d-positive.
skeletogenic cell that secretes dentine matrix, is derived from odontogenic papilla. embedded in dentine tissue, and is the transformation of a non-terminally differentiated odontoblast cell.
a cell of a layer of transitional epithelium in the wall of the bladder, ureter, and renal pelvis, external to the lamina propria.

a cell capable of producing epinephrine. epiniphrine is synthesized from norepiniphrine by the actions of the phenylethanolamine n-methyltransferase enzyme, which is expressed in the adrenal glands, androgenic neurons, and in other cell types.
an auditory hair cell located in the macula that is sensitive to auditory stimuli.
a cell of the embryo.
a fibroblast that is part of lung.

sperm: activated type ii nk t cell
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a type ii nk t cell that has been recently activated, secretes interferon-gamma and interleukin-4, and has the phenotype cd69-positive and downregulated nk markers.

an eosinophil with a ring-shaped nucleus that is resident in the lung parenchyma. in mouse, lung parenchyma resident eosinophils are il-5-independent siglec-f(intermediate) cd62l+ cd101(low). in human, they are siglec-8+ cd62l+ il-3r(low).

a fully differentiated basophil, a granular leukocyte with an irregularly shaped, pale-staining nucleus that is partially constricted into two lobes, and with cytoplasm that contains coarse granules of variable size. basophils contain vasoactive amines such as histamine and serotonin, which are released on appropriate stimulation.
an otic fibrocyte that underlies the stria vascularis and is part of a mesenchymal gap junction network that regulates ionic homeostasis of the endolymph.
a retinal ganglion a2 cell with dendrites terminating in s2.
a dendritic cell with the phenotype hla-dra-positive.

a neuron of the dorsal cochlear nucleus with spiny dendrites that receive input from the axons of granule cells and with axons that release gaba and glycine onto cartwheel, pyramidal and giant cell targets.
an undifferentiated cell of the prostate epithelium that lacks secretory activity.

sperm: fibroblast of subepithelial connective tissue of prostatic gland
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a fibroblast that is part of the subepithelial connective tissue of prostatic gland.
a monostratified retinal ganglion cell that has a small soma, a small dendrite field with a dense dendrite arbor, and post synaptic terminals in sublaminer layer s2 and s3.
a cultured cell that is freshly isolated from a organismal source, or derives in culture from such a cell prior to the culture being passaged.
any microvascular endothelial cell that is part of a brain.
the peripheral receptor for pain. includes receptors which are sensitive to painful mechanical stimuli, extreme heat or cold, and chemical stimuli. all mammalian nociceptors are free nerve endings.
a photoreceptor cell that is sensitive to green light.
a mesenchymal stem cell capable of developing into blood vessel endothelium.
a fibroblastic reticular cell found in the lymph node subcapsular sinus.

sperm: arcuate nucleus of hypothalamus kndy neuron
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a kndy neuron that is located in the arcuate nucleus of the hypothalamus.
a cell at the front of a migrating epithelial sheet.
a t cell that expresses an alpha-beta t cell receptor complex.
a female germ cell that has entered meiosis.
a mesothelial cell that is part of the parietal pleura.
a cell type that makes up the highly vascular membrane lining the marrow cavity of long bones.
an immature or mature cell of the first erythroid lineage to arise during embryonic development.
a stromal cell of the ovarian medulla.
an epithelial cell of the prostatic acinus.
mature cd11c-negative plasmacytoid dendritic cell is a cd11c-negative plasmacytoid dendritic cell is cd80-high, cd86-high, mhcii-high and is cd83-positive.
an amacrine cell with a wide dendritic field, dendrites in s3, and post-synaptic terminals in s3. dendrites of this cell type are straight and minimally branched.

a boettcher cell is a polyhedral cells on the basilar membrane of the cochlea, and is located beneath claudius cells. a boettcher cell is considered a supporting cell for the organ of corti, and is present only in the lower turn of the cochlea. these cells interweave with each other, and project microvilli into the intercellular space. because of their structural specialization, a boettcher cell is believed to play a significant role in the function of the cochlea. they demonstrate high levels of calmodulin, and may be involved in mediating ca(2+) regulation and ion transport.
an adult endothelial progenitor cell characterised in vivo by homing to ischemic sites and paracrine support of angiogenesis. they may form discrete colonies.

sperm: epithelial cell of stratum germinativum of esophagus
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a basal cell that is part of the epithelium of esophagus.

sperm: cd4-positive, cxcr3-negative, ccr6-negative, alpha-beta t cell
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a cd4-positive, alpha-beta t cell that has the phenotype cxcr3-negative, ccr6-negative.

a lymphocyte found in adipose tissue that lacks lineage markers of other lymphocytes but is capable of mediating th2 cytokine responses. this cell type is found in fat associated lymphoid clusters, proliferates in response to il2 and produce large amounts of th2 cytokines such as il5, il6 and il13
a fibroblast that is part of upper back skin.
a nucleated precursor of an erythrocyte that lacks hematopoietic lineage markers.
a retinal cell that is immature or undifferentiated.
any serous secreting cell that is part of the tracheobronchial epithelium.
a plasmablast that secretes iga.
a chromaffin cell that is part of the right ovary.
a memory b cell with the phenotype igd-negative and cd27-negative.
a monostratified retinal ganglion cell with medium soma, sparse dendritic tree, and medium dendritic field.
a reticulocyte that is ly76-high and is kit-negative.
an epithelial cell of the distal convoluted tubule of the kidney that helps regulate systemic levels of potassium, sodium, calcium, and ph.
a bistratifed retinal ganglion cell that has small, symmetric dendritic fields that terminate in s1 and s4-s5.
a nuclear bag fiber that is sensitive mainly to the rate of change in muscle length.
a cell derived from the mesoderm that is located between the paraxial mesoderm and the lateral plate.
immature cd8 alpha-negative cd11b-positive dendritic cell is a cd8 alpha-negative cd11b-positive dendritic cell that is cd80-low, cd86-low, and mhcii-low.

a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a mature nk t cell that secretes interferon-gamma and enhances th1 immune responses.
a stem cell that can differentiate into a cardiac myocyte.
an insect immune cell that develops from plasmatocyte.
a martinotti neuron that has axons that form a horizontal ramification, making it t-shaped.
glandular cell of parathyroid epithelium. example: parathyroid chief cell and parathyroid oxyphil cells.
any cell in a salivary gland.

an alpha-beta t cell expressing nk call markers that is cd1d restricted and expresses a diverse tcr repertoire. type ii nkt cells do not become activated by alpha-galactosylceramide when presented by cd1d.
an immature alpha-beta t-cell that express egr2. these cells give rise to t cells expressing nk markers.
a fibroblast that is located in the renal cortical interstitium.
a transit amplifying cell that is located in the anorectum.
any vein endothelial cell that is part of a hindlimb stylopod.

a small pre-b-ii cell is a pre-b-ii cell that is rag1-positive, rag2-positive, pre-bcr-negative, and bcr-negative, is not proliferating, and carries a dna rearrangement of one or more immunoglobulin light chain genes.
an endorphine cell that secretes enkephalin.
an amicrine that has a medium dendritic field.
a myeloblast committed to the basophil lineage.
an undifferentiated cell produced by early cleavages of the fertilized egg (zygote).

an interneuron (also called relay neuron, association neuron or local circuit neuron) is a multipolar neuron which connects afferent neurons and efferent neurons in neural pathways. like motor neurons, interneuron cell bodies are always located in the central nervous system (cns).

sperm: effector memory cd4-positive, alpha-beta t cell, terminally differentiated
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a cd4-positive, alpha beta memory t cell with the phenotype cd45ra-positive, cd45ro-negative, and ccr7-negative.
mature cd8 alpha-negative cd11b-positive dendritic cell is a cd8 alpha-negative cd11b-positive dendritic cell that is cd80-high, cd86-high, mhcii-high and is cd83-positive.
a nk1.1-positive t cell that is ly49h-positive.
any of the immature forms of a basophil, in which basophilic specific granules are present but other phenotypic features of the mature form may be lacking.
an epithelial cell of the lung.
a ciliated cell of the bronchus.
a spiral ganglion neuron that innervates inner hair cells. type 1 spiral ganglion neurons are myelinated and bipolar.
a retinal ganglion cell c outer that has symmetrical and dense dendritic dendritic tree with a large dendritic field.
a basal cell that is part of the urothelium.

sperm: endothelial cell of high endothelial venule
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a venule endothelial cell that is cubodial, expresses leukocyte-specific receptors, and allows for passage of lymphocytes into bloodstream.
a type of lymphocyte whose defining characteristic is the expression of a t cell receptor complex.
any microvascular endothelial cell that is part of a urinary bladder.
a cd11c-low plasmacytoid dendritic cell that is cd8alpha-negative and cd4-positive.

a thymic epithelial cell type with low nuclear and cytoplasmic electrondensity. has a round, euchromatic nucleus and occurs in small groups at the corticomedullary junction or scattered singly in the medulla.
cell that has the potential to form a skeletal cell type (e.g. cells in periosteum, cells in marrow) and produce extracellular matrix (often mineralized) and skeletal tissue (often mineralized).

a lymph node macrophage found in the subcapsular sinus of lymph nodes that participates in sensing, clearance, and antigen presentation of lymph-borne particulate antigens. this macrophage is capable of activating invaraint nkt cells and is cd169-positive.

a neurosecretory neuron residing mainly in the hypothalamic supraoptic and paraventricular nuclei and in a number of smaller accessory cell groups between these two nuclei, that is capable of secreting the hormones oxytocin or vasopressin, and sometimes both, into the systemic circulation.

sperm: vein endothelial cell of respiratory system
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a(n) vein endothelial cell that is part of a(n) respiratory system.
a cell whose primary function is to provide structural support, to provide strength and physical integrity to the organism.
an innate lymphoid cell that constituitively expresses rorgt and is capable of expressing il17a and/or il-22.

a specialized type of cd4 positive t cell, the follicular helper t cell (tfh cell), that upregulates cxcr5 expression to enable its follicular localization. these specialised t cells reside in the germinal center of the lymph node.
a fibroblast of the aortic adventitia.

sperm: enterocyte of epithelium proper of jejunum
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: an enterocyte that is part of the epithelium proper of jejunum.

a double negative post-natal thymocyte that has a t cell receptor consisting of a gamma chain that does not contain a vgamma2 segment, and a delta chain. this cell type is cd4-negative, cd8-negative and cd24-positive.
a male germ cell that develops from the haploid secondary spermatocytes. without further division, spermatids undergo structural changes and give rise to spermatozoa.
a tissue-resident macrophage found in the central nervous system.
a stem cell from which all cells of the body can form.
a cell that has a filiform extrusion of the cell surface.
a tall supporting cell that is arranged in rows adjacent to the last row of outer phalangeal cells. this cell type constitutes the outer border of the organ of corti.
an epithelial cell of the kidney cortex.
a goblet cell that is part of the epithelium of principal gastric gland.
a fibroblast that is part of the areolar connective tissue.
brush cell of the epithelium in the trachea.
a nk1.1-positive t cell that is ly49d-negative.
a preadipocyte that is part of the breast.
a polarized cell that is juxtaposed to fibrocytes in the underlying spiral ligament. this cell type secretes potassium ions derived from fibrocytes through gap junctions.

specialized elongated ventricular ependymal cell that has processes that extend to the outer, or pial, surface of the cns. resemble spongioblasts seen in developing brain. found in the adult brain in the third ventricle, cerebral aqueduct, spinal canal and floor of the fourth ventricle.
a preadipocyte that is part of visceral tissue.

sperm: immature dendritic epithelial t cell precursor
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a double negative thymocyte that has a t cell receptor consisting of a gamma chain that has as part a vgamma3 segment, and a delta chain. this cell type is cd4-negative, cd8-negative and cd24-positive. this cell-type is found in the fetal thymus with highest numbers occurring at e17-e18.
squamous cell of oral epithelium.
a nucleated blood cell involved in coagulation, typically seen in birds and other non-mammalian vertebrates.
a peptide hormone secreting cell that secretes oxytocin stimulating hormone
a non-terminally differentiated cell that originates from the neural crest and differentiates into an iridophore.
a plasmablast that secretes igg.
a squamous cell that has keratin in the esophagus.
interneuromast cell is a neuroectodermal cell deposited by the migrating lateral line primordium between the neuromasts. interneuromast cells proliferate and migrate to form additional neuromasts.
a hematopoietic stem cell with long term self renewal capability. this cell is kit-positive, sca1-positive, cd150-positive, cd90-low, cd34-negative and flt3-negative.
epithelial cell derived from mesoderm or mesenchyme.
a retinal ganglion cell that has dendrites stratified in two layers of the inner-plexiform layer.
any fibroblast that is part of a optic choroid.
a pericyte of the decidual vasculature.
a pyramidal neuron which has a distinctive tuft formation, distal from the soma.
a phagocyte formed by the fusion of mononuclear phagocytes.
a spermatid in a late stage of maturation that has an elongated morphology and is transcriptionally inert when the acrosome is fully developed.
a beta motor neuron that innervates nuclear chain fibers.
a pyramidal neuron with soma located in the amygdala.
a gamma-delta t cell that has a mature phenotype. these cells can be found in tissues and circulation where they express unique tcr repertoire depending on their location.
a mature astrocyte that is capable of producing cytokines.

olfactory epithelial support cell is a columnar cell that extends from the epithelial free margin to the basement membrane of the olfactory epithelium. this cell type has a large, vertically, elongate, euchromatic nucleus, along with other nuclei, forms a layer superficial to the cell body of the receptor cell. sends long somewhat irregular microvilli into the mucus layer. at the base, with expanded end-feet containing numerous lamellated dense bodies resembling lipofuscin of neurons.
a precursor cell with a limited number of potential fates.
a cell that secretes insulin and is located towards the center of the islets of langerhans.
a small cell formed by the second meiotic division of oocytes. in mammals, the second polar body may fail to form unless the ovum has been penetrated by a sperm cell.
an extracellular matrix secreting cell that secretes glycocalyx.
a mesothelial cell that is part of the dura mater.
the exocrine cell of the prostate, this epithelial cell secretes prostatic acid phosphotase and psa, and is dependent on androgen hormones for survival.

type of radial astrocyte in the cerebellar cortex that have their cell bodies in the purkinje cell layer and processes that extend into the molecular layer, terminating with bulbous endfeet at the pial surface. bergmann glia express high densities of glutamate transporters that limit diffusion of the neurotransmitter glutamate during its release from synaptic terminals. besides their role in early development of the cerebellum, bergmann glia are also required for the pruning or addition of synapses.

a preadipocyte that is capable of differentiating into a brown adipocyte. this cell type expresses uncoupling protein-1, ppar-gamma, pr-domain-containing 16. and pgc-1alpha (peroxisome proliferator-activated receptor-gamma (ppargamma) coactivator-1alpha).
chemosensitive cells that innervate the vomernasal organ epithelium and are responsible for receiving and transmitting pheromone signals.
an erythrocyte lacking a nucleus.

sperm: kidney loop of henle thick ascending limb epithelial cell
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: an epithelial cell that is part of some loop of henle thick ascending limb. it is known in some mammalian species that this cell may express the na+-k+-2cl cotransporter (nkcc2) apically.
a hematopoietic stem cell from the aorta-gonad-mesonephros region of the developing embryo. first seen at e10.5 in mouse embryos. may give rise to fetal liver hsc.
a natural killer cell that is developmentally mature and expresses a variety of inhibitory and activating receptors that recognize mhc class i and other stress related molecules.
gr1-high monocyte that has a mhc-ii receptor complex.
cytoplasm that exhibits a characteristic staining and color, red or pink, with eosin stain.
an achromatic cell of the myeloid or lymphoid lineages capable of ameboid movement, found in blood or other tissue.

sperm: neuron of the dorsal spinal cord
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a cns neuron of the dorsal spinal cord.
a monostratified retinal ganglion cell with large soma and large dendritic field.

an off-bipolar neuron found in the retina and having connections with cone photoreceptors cells and neurons in the outer half of the inner plexiform layer. the dendritic tree is delicate and the dendritic tips appear small when compared with type 1 cells. the axon terminal is stratified and restricted to sublamina 2 of the inner plexiform layer.
