a fibroblast located in the portal triad. hepatic portal fibroblast are a non-parenchymal cell population located adjacent to bile duct epithelia in liver and are distinct from stellate cells. they differentiate into fibrogenic myofibroblasts during chronic injury states producing high levels of collagen.
a cell that is part of the nervous system.
an endocrine cell that secretes juvenile hormone.
a dermal dendritic cell isolated from skin draining lymph nodes that is langerin-positive, mhc-ii-positive, and cd4-negative and cd8a-negative.
a cd4-positive, alpha-beta t cell that cooperates with other lymphocytes via direct contact or cytokine release to initiate a variety of immune functions.
a cone cell that detects ultraviolet (uv) wavelength light.

a gabaergic cortical interneuron that is strongly labelled for 7 nachrs. these cells have soma found in l1 and have multipolar dendrites with vertically descending axonal collaterals that project deep into the column, usually branching and terminating in l5a.

sperm: enterocyte of epithelium proper of duodenum
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: an enterocyte that is part of the epithelium proper of duodenum.

an immature b cell that is igm-positive, cd45r-positive, cd43-low, cd25-negative, and cd127-negative. this cell type has also been described as being aa4-positive, igm-positive, cd19-positive, cd43-low/negative, and hsa-positive.

sperm: corticothalamic val/vm projecting glutamatergic neuron of the primary motor cortex
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a corticothalamic-projecting glutamatergic neuron that is located in l6 and lower l5 of the primary motor cortex, with a pyramidal morphology and mostly untufted apical dendrites terminating in midcortical layers. ct val/vm (ventroanterior-ventrolateral complex/ventromedial nucleus) cells have a near tonic firing pattern and are distinguished from l6 it neurons by a lower inter-spike interval adaptation index.
a somatic stem cell that is part of the epidermis.

a cell involved in transporting nutrients, minerals, water, gases and other chemicals between cells for a variety of purposes including conveying nutrition to other tissues, removing waste products from the tissues, conveying gases for respiration, distributing heat and repelling invasion of foreign substances.

sperm: clear cell of eccrine sweat gland
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a sweat producing cell of eccrine sweat glands. pyramidal in shape, with its base resting on the basal lamina or myoepitheliocytes, and its microvillus-covered apical plasma membrane line up the intercellular canaliculi. cell is not stained by hematoxylin or eosin.

sperm: kit-positive, cd34-negative megakaryocyte erythroid progenitor cell
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a megakaryocyte erythroid progenitor cell that is kit-positive and is sca1-negative, cd34-negative, cd90-negative, il7r-alpha-negative and fcgr ii/iii-low.
any interneuron that is part of a spinal cord ventral column.
a fibroblast located between thymic lobules.
an epithelial cell that is part of the lacrimal duct.
a visceromotor motor neuron whose soma is located in the hindbrain, and which synapses to parasympathetic neurons that innervate tear glands, sweat glands, and the smooth muscles of the head.

a mesenchymal cell found in the developing heart and that develops into some part of the heart. these cells derive from intra- and extra-cardiac sources, including the endocardium, epicardium, neural crest, and second heart field.

skeletogenic cell that is terminally differentiated, secretes an avascular, gag-rich matrix, is embedded in cartilage tissue matrix, retains the ability to divide, and develops from a chondroblast cell.
a amacrine cell with a small dendritic field and post-synaptic terminals in s1, s2, s3, and s4. ab diffuse-1 amacrine cells have a tent-shaped dendritic arbor and undulate dendrites.
a bipolar neuron found in the retina that is synapsed by rod photoreceptor cells but not by cone photoreceptor cells. these neurons depolarize in response to light.

sperm: l6 intratelencephalic projecting glutamatergic neuron of the primary motor cortex
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: an intratelencephalic-projecting glutamatergic neuron with a soma found in l6 of the primary motor cortex. these cells are short untufted pyramidal cells, which could be stellate or inverted.

a skeletal muscle fiber that is part of a muscle spindle. these are specialized muscle fibers that serve as proprioceptors, detecting the amount and rate of change in length of a muscle. they are innervated by both sensory neurons and motor neurons (gamma and beta motorneurons, collectively referred to as fusimotor neurons).
cytoplasm that exhibits molecular interaction for basic dyes under specific ph conditions.
a cell that secretes glucagon.
a cell that is within the developmental lineage of gametes and is able to pass along its genetic material to offspring.
a smooth muscle cell that is part of the ciliary body.
an amacrine cell with a medium dendritic field and post-synaptic terminals in s2, and in s3-s4.
any animal cell containing pigment granules.

sperm: b cell of medullary sinus of lymph node
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a b cell found in the lymph node medullary sinus.
a memory b cell arising in the germinal center that is igd-negative and has undergone somatic mutation of the variable region of the immunoglobulin heavy and light chain genes.
a goblet cell that is part of the epithelium of trachea.
a specialized cell involved in sensory perception of smell.
an undifferentiated germ cell that proliferates rapidly and gives rise to oocytes.
gr1-low non-classical monocyte that has high surface expression of a mhc-ii complex.
a multifate stem cell found in skeletal muscle than can differentiate into many different cell types, including muscle. distinct cell type from satellite cell.
an astrocyte of the spinal cord.

a promyelocyte committed to the neutrophil lineage. this cell type is gata-1-positive, c/ebpa-positive, aml-1-positive, mpo-positive, has low expression of pu.1 transcription factor and lacks lactotransferrin expression.

a stem cell from which all cells of the lymphoid and myeloid lineages develop, including blood cells and cells of the immune system. hematopoietic stem cells lack cell markers of effector cells (lin-negative). lin-negative is defined by lacking one or more of the following cell surface markers: cd2, cd3 epsilon, cd4, cd5 ,cd8 alpha chain, cd11b, cd14, cd19, cd20, cd56, ly6g, ter119.

a mesothelial fibroblast of the arachnoid barrier layer. arachnoid barrier cells make up the tight-junctioned layer in the leptomeninx that functions as the physiologic barrier between the cerebrospinal fluid in the subarachnoid space and the fenestrated capillaries in the dura.

a multi-fate stem cell that is the source of cells for growth of the mammary gland during puberty and gestation. this cell type gives rise to both the luminal and myoepithelial cell types of the gland, and have been shown to have the ability to regenerate the entire organ in mice. this cell type also plays an important role in carcinogenesis of the breast. this cell type is lin-, cd24-positive, cd29-hi.
a g4 retinal ganglion cell that has post sympatic terminals in sublaminar layers s3 and s4 and is depolarized by illumination of its receptive field center.
a granulocyte monocyte progenitor that is kit-positive, cd34-positive, fc-gamma receptor ii/ii-positive, and is sca-1-negative, il7ra-negative, cxc3r1-negative, and cd90-negative.
an epithelial cell of the kidney.

sperm: posterior lateral line neuromast mantle cell
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: any neuromast mantle cell that is part of a posterior lateral line.
a common myeloid progenitor that is cd34-positive, cd38-positive, il3ra-low, cd10-negative, cd7-negative, cd45ra-negative, and il-5ralpha-negative.
a goblet cell that is part of the small intestine.
an enteroendocrine cell that is located in the small intestine.

hematopoietic cells resident in the bone marrow. include: hematopoietic stem cells (lymphoid stem cells and myeloid stem cells) and the precursor cells for thrombocytes, erythrocytes, basophils, neutrophils, eosinophils, monocytes and lymphocytes.

sperm: nonkeratinized epithelial cell of anal column
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a nonkeratinized epithelial cell of the anal canal.
a purkinje myocyte that is part of the atrioventricular node.
a mesenchymal stem cell of the amnion membrane.
a trophoblast cell that is not part of a placental villous.

sperm: mesothelial cell of anterior chamber of eye
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a mesothelial cell that is part of the anterior chamber of eyeball.
any leukocyte that is part of a spleen.
a fibroblast of pulmonary artery.
a mono-stratified retinal ganglion cell that has a large dendritic field and a sparse dendritic arbor with post synaptic terminals in sublaminar layer s4.

sperm: vgamma5-negative cd8alpha alpha positive gamma-delta intraepithelial t cell
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a cd8alpha alpha positive gamma-delta intraepithelial t cell that does not express a tcr partially encoded by the vgamma5 gene segment.

a glial cell that develops from a schwann cell precursor. the immature schwann cell is embedded among neurons (axons) with minimal extracellular spaces separating them from nerve cell membranes and has a basal lamina. cells can survive without an axon present. immature schwann cell can be found communally ensheathing large groups of axons.
the neurons that utilize glycine as a neurotransmitter.
an m7 retinal ganglion cells with synaptic terminals in s2 and is depolarized by decreased illumination of their receptive field center
a pericyte cell that is part of a lung.
any hepatocyte that is part of the liver lobule centrilobular region. these cells are the primary location for the biotransformation of drugs.
a secondary lens fiber cell that lacks a nucleus.
an enteroendocrine cell that stores and secretes ghrelin.
the output neuron of the cerebellar cortex.

an immature cell of the conventional dendritic cell lineage, characterized by high levels of antigen uptake via endocytosis, macropinocytosis, and phagocytosis, and typically found resident in the tissues. markers for this cell are cd80-low, cd86-low, and mhc-ii-low.

a segmented neutrophilic cell of the bone marrow reserve pool that expresses cd11b (integrin alpha-m) and high levels of cd16 (low affinity immunoglobulin gamma fc region receptor iii) on its cell surface.
a tissue-resident macrophage resident found in the thymus, involved in the clearance of apoptotic thymocytes.

an elicited macrophage that is recruited into the tissues in response to injury and infection as part of an inflammatory response, expresses high levels of pro-inflammatory cytokines, ros and no, and shows potent microbicidal activity.
a cell secreting sebun, an oily substance secreted by sebaceous glands, composed of keratin, fat, and cellular debris.
an epithelial somatic cell associated with a maturing oocyte.
a cell whose primary function is to protect the organism.

sperm: fibroblast of connective tissue of prostate
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a fibroblast that is part of the connective tissue of prostate.
a neuron with a small cell body that is located in a koniocellular layer of the lateral geniculate nucleus (lgn).
a pulmonary interstitial fibroblast that is part of the alveolus and contains lipid droplets.

sperm: endothelial cell of respiratory system lymphatic vessel
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: an endothelial cell that is part of a respiratory system lymphatic vessel.

one of three types of epithelial cells that populate the parathyroid gland. cytological characteristics intermediate between those of the chief cell and of the oxyphil cell. because only one hormone is produced, the three cell forms are widely believed to be different phases in the life cycle of a single cell type, with the chief cell being its physiologically active stage.
a cell of an organism that does not pass on its genetic material to the organism's offspring (i.e. a non-germ line cell).
a cell whose primary function is to prevent the transport of stuff across compartments.
a thymic medullary epithelial cell that expresses muscle-specific biomarkers.
a cell secreting tears, the fluid secreted by the lacrimal glands. this fluid moistens the conjunctiva and cornea.
an amicrine that has a wide dendritic field.

a cd4-positive, cxcr5-positive, ccr7-negative alpha-beta t cell located in follicles of secondary lymph nodes that is bcl6-high, icos-high and pd1-high, and stimulates follicular b cells to undergo class-switching and antibody production.

a neuroepithelial cells that occurs singly or in small groups, close to the outer follicular borders but within the follicular basement membrane of the thyroid. expresses a form of the neural cell adhesion molecule (n-cam) on their surface. secretes calcitonin, 5-hydroxytryptamine and dopamine.
a short lived plasma cell that secretes igg.
a cell type that can give rise to basophil and mast cells. this cell is cd34-positive, cd117-positive, cd125-positive, fceria-negative, and t1/st2-negative, and expresses gata-1, gata-2, c/ebpa

a small, narrow, peg-shaped epithelial cell with little cytoplasm that is part of oviduct epithelium. this cell is rarer than the ciliated and secretory epithelial cells of the fallopian tube epithelium and is often found intercalated between them. peg cells are generally distributed basally along the epithelium and have been found in high concentrations at the fimbriated, distal end of the fallopian tube in humans. it may have a regenerative/stem-cell function. in humans, markers include epcam, cd44, and itga6.
a type of enteroendocrine cell found in the stomach that secretes glucagon.
a columnar/cuboidal epithelial cell that secretes cerebrospinal fluid.
a muscle cell that develops tension more slowly than a fast-twitch fiber.
a thymocyte found in the fetal thymus.
a fetal and neonatal heart cell that undergoes proliferation and is not yet terminally differentiated into a binucleate or a multinucleate cardiac myocyte.

sperm: microfold cell of epithelium proper of duodenum
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a m cell that is part of the epithelium proper of duodenum.
a basket cell with axonal arbors composed of frequent, short, curvy axonal branches that tend to be near their somata and within the same layer.

a cell with extensive dendritic processes found in the b cell areas (primary follicles and germinal centers) of lymphoid tissue. they are unrelated to the dendritic cell associated with t cells. follicular dendritic cells have fc receptors and c3b receptors, but unlike other dendritic cells, they do not process or present antigen in a way that allows recognition by t cells. instead, they hold antigen in the form of immune complexes on their surfaces for long periods and can present antigen to b cells during an immune response.
specialized ependymal cell that produces the cerebrospinal fluid from the blood and secretes it into the lumen of the brain and spinal chord.
an intermediate monocyte that is gr1-positive, cd43-positive.
an interneuron that has its soma located in the cerebral cortex.
an interrenal chromaffin cell found in teleosts that contain heterogeneous vesicles with electron-dense granules located asymmetrically within the vesicular membrane.
a cell with a single nucleus.
a gabaergic cortical interneuron that expresses cck. l5/6 cck cells have soma found mainly in l5 and l6 and have large axonal arborization.

a cell that is part of pigmented ciliary epithelium. this cell type uptakes sodium and chloride ions from stromal interstitium and passes the ions to non-pigmented ciliary epithelial cells via gap junctions.
any endothelial cell of artery that is part of a umbilical cord.
an enteroendocrine cell that produces glucagon.
a type of enteocrine cell found in the periphery of the islets of langerhans that secretes glucagon.
a non-nucleated disk-shaped cell formed by extrusion from megakaryocytes, found in the blood of all mammals, and mainly involved in blood coagulation.
a gamma-delta receptor that expresses vgamma1.1-vdelta6.3 chains in the t-cell receptor.
a stromal cell that is part of a bone marrow.
any basket cell that is part of a neocortex.

an immature myeloid leukocyte of heterogeneous phenotype found particularly in cancer and sepsis patients that is capable of suppressing activity of t cells in ex vivo assays. this cell type is cd45-positive, cd11b-positive.

a cellular receptor which mediates the sense of temperature. thermoreceptor cells in vertebrates are mostly located under the skin. in mammals there are separate types of thermoreceptors for cold and for warmth and pain receptor cells which detect cold or heat extreme enough to cause pain.
a alpha-beta t cell that has a mature phenotype.
an epithelial cell that is part of a duct.

specialized epithelial cells involved in the maintenance of osmotic homeostasis. they are characterized by abundant mitochondria and ion transporters. in amniotes, they are present in the renal system. in freshwater fish, ionocytes in the skin and gills help maintain osmotic homeostasis by absorbing salt from the external environment.
the subcutaneous mechanoreceptors that innervate tylotrich hair follicles.
a cd8-positive, alpha-beta t cell that regulates overall immune responses as well as the responses of other t cell subsets through direct cell-cell contact and cytokine release.
an enteroendocrine cell of the small intestine that secretes motilin.
a monocyte that has characteristics of both patrolling and inflammatory monocytes.
a common myeloid progenitor that is kit-positive and cd34-positive, il7ra-negative, and is sca1-low and fcgr2-low and fcgr3-low.

sperm: fibroblast of dense regular elastic tissue
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a fibroblast that is part of the dense regular elastic tissue.
a gabaergic inhibitory neuron that is derived from the midbrain.

sperm: external limiting cell of vestibular epithelium
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: an external limiting cell found in the vestibular epithelium.
a glutamatergic neuron located in the cerebral cortex that projects to the thalamus.
an enterocyte that is a part of a vermiform appendix.
a connective tissue cell found in bone.
a fungal cell with two or more genetically distinct nuclei.

sperm: naive thymus-derived cd8-positive, alpha-beta t cell
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a cd8-positive, alpha-beta t cell that has not experienced activation via antigen contact and has the phenotype cd45ra-positive, ccr7-positive and cd127-positive. this cell type is also described as being cd25-negative, cd62l-high and cd44-low.
the human equivalent of a dn3 thymocyte. these thymocytes finish the process of beta selection.
a fibroblast that is part of villous mesenchyme.
any melanocyte that is part of a prepuce of penis.
an cd38-negative unswitched memory b cell is an unswitched memory b cell that has the phenotype cd38-negative, igd-positive, cd138-negative, and igg-negative.

sperm: cd34-negative, cd117-positive innate lymphoid cell, human
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: an innate lymphoid cell in the human with the phenotype cd34-negative, cd117-positive, and a precusor to nk cells, ilc2 cells, and ilc3 cells.
a vgamma1.1-positive, vdelta6.3-positive thymocyte that is cd24-positive.
an epithelial cell that has its apical plasma membrane folded into microvilli to provide ample surface for the absorption of nutrients from the intestinal lumen.

sperm: neuroendocrine cell of epithelium of crypt of lieberkuhn
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a(n) neuroendocrine cell that is part of a(n) epithelium of crypt of lieberkuhn.
a sst gabaergic cortical interneuron that also expresses chodl. these neurons are rare and correspond to the only known cortical interneurons with long-range projection.

sperm: basal proper cell of olfactory epithelium
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a flat or angular epithelial cell with condensed nuclei and darkly staining cytoplasm containing numerous intermediate filaments inserted into desmosomes contacting surrounding supporting cells. lie in contact with the basal lamina of olfactory epithelium.
a neural crest cell that gives rise to cells of the enteric nervous system.
one of the two haploid cells into which a primary spermatocyte divides, and which in turn gives origin to spermatids.

a precursor in the granulocytic series, being a cell intermediate in development between a myeloblast and myelocyte, that has distinct nucleoli, a nuclear-to-cytoplasmic ratio of 5:1 to 3:1, and containing a few primary cytoplasmic granules. markers for this cell are fucosyltransferase fut4-positive, cd33-positive, integrin alpha-m-negative, low affinity immunoglobulin gamma fc region receptor iii-negative, and cd24-negative.
a cd11b-positive dendritic cell that is cd11b-low, cd45-positive, mhc-ii-high and cd103-positive that is located in the liver.
any dopaminergic neuron that is part of a midbrain.
an enteroendocrine cell found in the ileum and jejunum that produces neurotensin.

a eosinophil precursor in the granulocytic series, being a cell intermediate in development between a eosinophilic myelocyte and a band form eosinophil. the nucleus becomes indented where the indentation is smaller than half the distance to the farthest nuclear margin. chromatin becomes coarse and clumped. specific granules predominate while primary granules are rare. markers are integrin alpha-m-positive, fucosyltransferase fut4-positive, low affinity immunoglobulin gamma fc region receptor iii-positive, cd33-positive, cd24-positive and aminopeptidase n-negative.
an ionocyte that is part of the lung epithelium. the cells from this type are major sources of the cftr protein in human and mice.
a bushy cell that receives only few large excitatory endbulb synapses from auditory nerves. spherical bush cells give excitatory input to the lateral and medial parts of the superior olive.

sperm: myoepithelial cell of main lactiferous duct
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a myoepithelial cell that is part of the main lactiferous duct.
an intestinal tuft cell that is a part of a vermiform appendix.

sperm: brush border cell of the proximal tubule
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a brush border epithelial cell located in the proximal tubule of the kidney that detects fluid flow.

sperm: cd11b-low, cd103-negative, langerin-negative lymph node dendritic cell
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a langerin-negative lymph node dendritic cell that is cd103-negative and cd11b-low.
a dermal dendritic cell that is cd1a-positive and cd14-negative.
a fast muscle fiber cell that stores energy in the form of glycogen and creatine phosphate.
a mature b cell that produces cytokines that can influence cd4 t cell differentiation.
the reproductive cell in multicellular organisms.

an inactive fibroblast. cytoplasm is sparse, endoplasmic reticulum is scanty with flattened nucleus. term used by some histologists. when fibroblasts become relatively inactive in fiber formation. however, this cell has the potential for fibrogenesis in quiescent connective tissue of the adult, as well as during development, other histologists prefer to use the term fibroblast in all circumstances. these cells represent ~0.5% of peripheral blood leukocytes.

a basophil precursor in the granulocytic series, being a cell intermediate in development between a basophilic myelocyte and a band form basophil. the nucleus becomes indented where the indentation is smaller than half the distance to the farthest nuclear margin. chromatin becomes coarse and clumped. specific granules predominate while primary granules are rare. markers are cd11b-positive, cd15-positive, cd16-positive, cd24-positive, cd33-positive, and cd13-positive.
a small pre-b cell that is cd22-positive and cd38-low.
a cell that supports the development of a gamete by providing it cytoplasmic material (including entire organelles) by direct cross-membrane channels (del pino, 2021).
a motor neuron that innervates a skeletal muscle. these motor neurons are all excitatory and cholinergic.
a mesothelial cell that is part of the epicardium.
an otic fibrocyte that underlies the spiral prominence and is part of a mesenchymal gap junction network that regulates ionic homeostasis of the endolymph.
the stem cell from which glial precursor cell arises from.
a cardiac myocyte of the interatrial region of the heart.
an undifferentiated columnar cell of the bronchus epithelium
a cell found within the adrenal medulla that secrete biogenic amine hormones upon stimulation.
a fat cell of perirenal fat tissue.

sperm: type 1 vestibular sensory cell of epithelium of crista of ampulla of semicircular duct of membranous labyrinth
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a type i vestibular sensory cell that is part of the epithelium of crista of ampulla of semicircular duct of membranous labyrinth.
a circulating endothelial cell of the phenotype cd146-positive, cd105-positive, cd45-negative. this cell type is indicative of recent vascular damage.
a neuron that is capable of some neurotansmission by glutamate secretion.
a goblet cell located in the nasal epithelium.
a neuroglial cell of the peripheral nervous system inside the basal lamina of the neuromuscular junction providing chemical and physical support to the synapse.
any cell in the compound eye, a light sensing organ composed of ommatidia.

sperm: l6 tyrosine hydroxylase sst gabaergic cortical interneuron (mmus)
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a sst gabaergic cortical interneuron found in l6 that expresses tyrosine hydroxylase. l6 th+ sst cells have mostly local axonal arborization within l6.
an epithelial cell that secretes cuticle.
a myeloblast committed to the eosinophil lineage.

sperm: type 2 vestibular sensory cell of epithelium of crista of ampulla of semicircular duct of membranous labyrinth
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a type ii vestibular sensory cell that is part of the epithelium of crista of ampulla of semicircular duct of membranous labyrinth.
an ecto-epithelial cell of the prostate gland that secretes hormones.
a fibroblastic reticular cell found in the lymph node germinal center dark zone (b cell zone).
a myoblast that differentiates into skeletal muscle fibers.

a retinal ganglion cell ocated in the ganglion cell layer of the retina and projects to magnocellular cells in the lateral geniculate nucleus (lgn) as part of the magnocellular pathway in the visual system. they have large cell bodies as well as extensive branching dendrite networks and as such have large receptive fields.
an astrocyte that is part of the hippocampus.
a thick walled spore that stores and protects one or more nuclei following sexual reproduction in an ascomycete.
an immature cd14-positive dermal dendritic cell is cd80-low, cd86-low, and mhcii-low.
a central nervous system macrophage found in small blood vessels in the brain. markers include cd14+cd16+cd163+.
a progenitor cell committed to myeloid lineage, including the megakaryocyte and erythroid lineages. these cells are cd34-positive, and express gata1, gata2, c/ebpa, and pu.1.
a fetal liver derived enucleated erythrocyte. this erythrocyte resembles adult erythrocytes in that they are small (3- to 6- times smaller than primitive erythrocytes) and produce adult hemaglobins.
cylindrical spore formed by development and compartmentation of hyphae. the hyphae are often supporting blastoconidiophores.
a cd8-positive, alpha-beta t cell that is capable of killing target cells in an antigen specific manner with the phenotype perforin-positive and granzyme b-positive.
an auditory epithelial support cell that surrounds the nerve fibers and synapses of the auditory inner hair cells.

an interstitial cell that is part of a cardiac valve leaflet. along with valve endothelial cells, a valve interstitial cell maintains tissue homeostasis for the function of cardiac valves through secreting biochemical signals, matrix proteins and matrix remodeling enzymes.
a mesothelial cell that is part of the small intestine.
epithelial cell that is part of the colon epithelium.

sperm: cd24-positive cd38-negative igg-negative class switched memory b cell
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: an cd24-positive cd38-negative igg-negative memory b cell is a cd38-negative igg-negative class switched memory b cell that lacks igg on the cell surface with the phenotype cd24-positive, cd38-negative, and igg-negative.

sperm: kidney outer medulla collecting duct principal cell
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: principal cell that is part of some outer medullary collecting duct. it is known in some mammalian species that this cell may express the epithelial sodium channel (enac).
a cell in vitro that has undergone physical changes as a consequence of a deliberate and specific experimental procedure.
a proerythoblast that is kit-low, lyg76-positive, and cd71-positive.
any microvascular endothelial cell that is part of a prostate gland.
any skin fibroblast that is part of a upper leg skin.

a giioblast cell that develops from a migratory neural crest cell. the scp is embedded among neurons (axons) with minimal extracellular spaces separating them from nerve cell membranes and has no basal lamina. in rodents scps are the only cells in the schwann cell linage that expresses cdh19.
glial cell of lateral ventricle.

sperm: superficial external epithelial cell of tympanic membrane
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a cell type found on the superficial layer of the external side of the tympanic membrane. this cell-type lacks a nucleus.
glandular cell of oviduct epithelium. example: peg cells, ciliated cells.

a cell found throughout the gastrointestinal tract and in the pancreas. they secrete somatostatin in both an endocrine and paracrine manner. somatostatin inhibits gastrin, cholecystokinin, insulin, glucagon, pancreatic enzymes, and gastric hydrochloric acid. a variety of substances which inhibit gastric acid secretion (vasoactive intestinal peptide, calcitonin gene-related peptide, cholecystokinin, beta-adrenergic agonists, and gastric inhibitory peptide) are thought to act by releasing somatostatin.
a peptide hormone secreting cell that secretes substance p.
myeloid mononuclear recirculating leukocyte that can act as a precursor of tissue macrophages, osteoclasts and some populations of tissue dendritic cells.
a thymic epithelial cell located at the corticomedullary junction.
a mesodermal cell that is part of the splanchnic layer of lateral plate mesoderm.
an epithelial cell of the musculomembranous digestive tube extending from the mouth to the anus.
a naive regulatory t cell with the phenotype cd4-positive, cd25-positive, cd127lo, ccr4-positive, and cd45ro-negative.
a peptide hormone secreting cell that secretes androgen binding protein.

sperm: igd-positive cd38-positive igg memory b cell
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: an igd-positive cd38-positive igg memory b cell is a cd38-positive igg-positive class switched memory b cell that has class switched and expresses igd on the cell surface with the phenotype igd-positive, cd38-positive, and igg-positive.
a d cell located in the colon.
a d cell located in the pancreas. peripherally placed within the islets like type a cells. contains somatostatin.
a stem cell of embryonic origin.

sperm: smooth muscle cell of the brain vasculature
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a vascular associated smooth muscle cell of the brain vasculature.
a gabaergic neuron located in the cerebral cortex that expresses somatostatin (sst)
a lymphoid progenitor cell of the t cell lineage, with some lineage specific marker expression, but not yet fully committed to the t cell lineage.

sperm: l2/3 intratelencephalic projecting glutamatergic neuron of the primary motor cortex
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: an intratelencephalic-projecting glutamatergic neuron with a soma found in cortical layer 2/3.
a motile sperm cell that contain no f-actin, and their motility is powered by a dynamic filament system.
a renal intercalated cell that secretes base and reabsorbs acid in the distal segments of the kidney tubule to maintain acid/base balance.

a glial cell that is part of the perineurium. this cell type has thin long bipolar cytoplasmic processes, pinocytotic vesicles, fragments of external lamina and/or external lamina-like material, attachment plaques, and desmosome-like junctions. perineurial cells historically have been referred to as fibroblasts because of shape. however, unlike fibroblasts, a perineurial cell: does not have a compact nucleus and large endoplasmic reticulum. does have a double basement membrane opposed to a single basal lamina. is carefully joined to other perineurial cells by tight junctions into a single sheet as opposed to arranged in a large mass. and finally, can surround a small axon bundle at a nerve terminal whereas a fibroblast cannot.
a myeloid dendritic cell with the phenotype hla-dra-positive.
a gabaergic interneuron whose soma is located in the cerebral cortex.

sperm: epithelial cell of external acoustic meatus
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: an epithelial cell that is part of the external acoustic meatus.

epithelioid macrophage is an activated macrophage that resembles an epithelial cell with finely granular, pale eosinophilic cytoplasm and central, ovoid nucleus (oval or elongate). this cell type is able to merge into one another to form aggregates. the presence of such aggregates may characterize some pathologic conditions, mainly granulomatous inflammation.
a short lived plasma cell that secretes igm.
a cell whose nucleus has two haploid genomes.

an epithelial cell of the intrahepatic portion of the bile duct. these cells are flattened or cuboidal in shape, and have a small nuclear-to-cytoplasmic ratio relative to large/extrahepatic cholangiocytes.
a cell that is capable of detection of a stimulus involved in sensory perception.

a lower motor neuron that innervates only intrafusal muscle fibers. unlike the alpha motor neurons, gamma motor neurons do not directly adjust the lengthening or shortening of muscles but function in adjusting the sensitivity of muscle spindles and in keeping muscle spindles taut, thereby allowing the continued firing of alpha neurons.
an inhibitory gabaergic interneuron found in the cerebellar cortex.
a precursor cell destined to differentiate into cardiac muscle cell.
a basket cell which has simpler dendritic arbors (compared to small or large basket cells), and an axonal plexus of intermediate density, composed of a few long, smooth axonal branches.
a lymphocyte of b lineage that is cd19-positive.
a trophoblast giant cell that is derived from ectoplacental cone and, later in gestation, the spongiotrophoblast.
a melanocyte that is part of the eyelid.
a preadipocyte that is part of subcutaneous tissue.

a pigment cell derived from the neural crest. the cell contains flat light-reflecting platelets, probably of guanine, in stacks called reflecting platelets or iridisomes. the color-generating components produce a silver, gold, or iridescent color.
neuron that is part of the enteric nervous system.
a conventional b cell subject to antigenic stimulation and dependent on t cell help and with a distinct surface marker expression pattern from b-1 b cells. these cells are cd43-negative.

an on-bipolar neuron found in the retina and having connections with cone photoreceptors cells and neurons in the inner half of the inner plexiform layer. this cell has the widest dendritic field and the widest axon terminal of all retinal bipolar cells. the axon terminal is delicate and stratified through sublaminae 4 and 5 of the inner plexiform layer.
an acidophilic cell of the anterior pituitary that produces growth hormone, somatotropin.

a gamma motor neuron that innervates static nuclear bag fibers (bag2 fibers) and increases their firing, in response to an increase in the magnitude of change in length, and controls the static sensitivity of the stretch reflex.

cell that is part of the vagal neural crest population. the vagal neural crest arises from the axial level of somites 1-7 and has been described as a hybrid between the head and the trunk populations.
a macrophage that suppresses immune responses.
a melanocyte that produces pigment within the hair follicle.
a hypothalamus kisspeptin neuron that coexpresses kisspeptin, neurokinin b and dynorphin.
glandular cell of exocrine pancreas epithelium. example: pancreatic acinar cell, glandular cells in pancreatic canaliculi, glandular cells in pancreatic ducts.
a cone cell that detects medium wavelength light. exact peak of spectra detected differs between species. in humans, spectra peaks at 534-545 nm.

cells of the uterine chorion that acquire specialized structural and/or functional features that characterize chorionic trophoblasts. these cells will migrate towards the spongiotrophoblast layer and give rise to syncytiotrophoblasts of the labyrinthine layer.
a dendritic cell arising in thymus that has the phenotype cd11c-positive, cd11b-negative, and cd45ra-negative.
a cell of the early embryo at the developmental stage in which the blastomeres, resulting from repeated mitotic divisions of the fertilized ovum (zygote), form a compact cell mass.
a cell which moves among different tissues of the body, via blood, lymph, or other medium.
a smooth muscle cell that is part of a placenta.

a fully differentiated neutrophil, a granular leukocyte having a nucleus with three to five lobes connected by slender threads, and cytoplasm containing fine inconspicuous granules and stainable by neutral dyes. they are produced in bone marrow at a rate of 5e10-10e10/day and have a half-life of 6-8 hours. neutrophils are cd15-positive, cd16-positive, cd32-positive, cd43-positive, cd181-positive, and cd182-positive.

sperm: paneth cell of epithelium of small intestine
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a paneth cell that is part of the epithelium of small intestine.
an epithelial cell of a skin gland.
a leukocyte that lacks granules.
a cell type that forms the boundary with the surrounding epithelium.

large intrinsic neuron located in the granule layer of the cerebellar cortex that extends its dendrites into the molecular layer where they receive contact from parallel fibers. the axon of the golgi cell ramifies densely in the granule layer and enters into a complex arrangement with mossy fiber terminals and granule cell dendrites to form the cerebellar glomerulus. llinas, walton and lang. in the synaptic organization of the brain. 5th ed. 2004.
skeletogenic cell that produces enamel, overlies the odontogenic papilla, and arises from the differentiation of a preameloblast cell.

sperm: inactive chief cell of parathyoid gland
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a parathyroid chief cell that is not actively secreting hormone. contains small golgi complexes with only a few grouped vesicles and membrane-bound secretory granules. glycogen and many lipofuscin granules abound but sacs of granular endoplasmic reticulum are rare and dispersed. in normal humans, inactive chief cells out number active chief cells in a ratio of 3-5:1.
a highly specialized cell type exclusive to and forming neuroepithelium of the saccus vasculosus, covering the caudal diverticulum of the infundibular recess.
an acinar cell of salivary gland.

sperm: cd8-positive, cxcr3-positive, alpha-beta regulatory t cell
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a cd8-positive alpha-beta-positive t cell with the phenotype cxcr3-positive and having suppressor function. they are capable of producing il-10, suppressing proliferation, and suppressing ifn-gamma production.
any fibroblast of lung that is part of a bronchus.

sperm: cd24-negative cd38-negative igg-negative class switched memory b cell
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a cd24-negative cd38-negative igg-negative memory b cell is a cd38-negative igg-negative class switched memory b cell that lacks igg on the cell surface with the phenotype cd24-negative, cd38-negative, and igg-negative.
a non-neuronal cell that surrounds the neuronal cell bodies of the ganglia.

sperm: transitional myocyte of atrial septal branch of anterior internodal tract
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a transitional myocyte that is part of the atrial septal branch of anterior internodal tract.

sperm: smooth muscle cell derived foam cell
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a type of foam cell derived from a smooth muscle cell containing lipids in small vacuoles and typically seen in atherolosclerotic lesions, as well as other conditions.
an immature b cell that is cd38-negative, cd10-low, cd21-low, and cd22-high.
a bistratified amacrine cell with a medium dendritic field, a flat and sparse dendritic arbor, and post-synaptic terminals at the intersections of s1 and s2, and s3 and s4.
a regular cardiac myocyte of the interventricular region of the heart.

a cell characteristically found lining hollow organs that are subject to great mechanical change due to contraction and distention. originally thought to represent a transition between stratified squamous and columnar epithelium.
a myoepithelial cell that is part of the mammary gland alveolus.
a cell that specializes in secretion of surfactant in the alveoli of the lung.

a large, multipolar lower motor neuron of the brainstem and spinal cord that innervates the extrafusal muscle fibers of skeletal muscle and are directly responsible for initiating their contraction. while their cell bodies are in the cns (in the anterior gray horn of the spinal cord), they are part of the somatic nervous system - a branch of the pns.

sperm: l6b subplate glutamatergic neuron of the primary motor cortex
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: an excitatory glutamatergic neuron transcriptomically related to the ct subclass, with a soma preferentially located in the bottom of l6 of the primary motor cortex.

sperm: immature nk t cell stage iv
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a cd24-low, cd44-positive, dx5-high, nk1.1-negative nk t cell.
an unconventional t lymphocyte population within the thymic medulla that is potentially a thymic resident population.
a photoreceptor cell that detects ultraviolet light.
an astrocyte of the forebrain.
an immature microglial cell with a ramified morphology.

a lymphocyte that is part of a peyer's patch. these cells have a major role in driving the immune response to antigens sampled from the intestinal lumen, and in regulating the formation of follicle-associated epithelium and m cells in peyer's patches by converting intestitial enterocytes into m cells.
a neuron whose cell body is within an autonomic ganglion.

sperm: nkp44-positive group 3 innate lymphoid cell, human
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a group 3 innate lymphoid cell in the human with the phenotype il-7ralpha-positive, and nkp44-positive.
cd8 alpha-negative cd11b-positive dendritic cell is a conventional dendritic cell that is cd11b-positive, cd4-positive and is cd205-negative and cd8 alpha-negative.

sperm: myoepithelial cell of intralobular lactiferous duct
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a myoepithelial cell that is part of the intralobular part of terminal lactiferous duct.
the flattened smooth myoepithelial cells of mesodermal origin that lie just outside the basal lamina of the seminiferous tubule.
a cone whose sensitivity measurements have an average spectral peak of 358.2 nm. these cones are described in rat.

sperm: cd16-positive, cd56-dim natural killer cell, human
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a mature natural killer cell that has the phenotype cd56-low, cd16-positive and which is capable of cytotoxicity and cytokine production.
a mature cd16-positive myeloid dendritic cell is cd80-high, cd83-positive, cd86-high, and mhcii-high.
an epithelial cell present in the trachea and bronchi. columnar in shape. generally lack cilia. immature forms of ciliated or secretory cells which have been formed from stem cells.
a glutamatergic neuron located in the cerebral cortex that projects axons locally rather than distantly.

a large epithelial cell found in the thymus. this cell type may internalize thymocytes through extensions of plasma membrane. the cell surface and cytoplasmic vacuoles of a thymic nurse cell express mhc class i and mhc class ii antigens. the interaction of these antigens with a developing thymocyte determines whether the thymocyte undergoes positive or negative selection.

sperm: stromal cell of lamina propria of small intestine
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a stromal cell found in the lamina propria of the small intestine.

sperm: smooth muscle cell of the pulmonary artery
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a smooth muscle of the pulmonary artery.
a hematopoietic stem cell of the placenta. this cell type is first observed e10.5 this cell type may give rise to fetal liver hematopoietic stem cells.
any native cell that is part of a inner cell mass.
a mature microglial cell that has changed shape to an amoeboid morphology and is capable of cytokine production and antigen presentation.

sperm: sensory neuron of dorsal root ganglion
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a sensory neuron of the dorsal root ganglia that senses body position and sends information about how much the muscle is stretched to the spinal cord.

a natural killer cell subset that is found in the decidual of the uterus and is cd56-high, galectin-1-positive and cd16-negative. this cell type represents the most abundant immune cell type in the decidual during the first trimester of pregnancy.

sperm: igg-negative class switched memory b cell
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a class switched memory b cell that lacks igg on the cell surface.

sperm: light chief cell of parathyroid gland
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a chief cell that is bigger than dark chief cells and has a larger and lighter nucleus and a cytoplasm with few granules.

a pro-b cell that is cd45r/b220-positive, cd43-positive, hsa-low, bp-1-negative and ly6c-negative. this cell type is also described as being lin-negative, aa4-positive, kit-positive, il7ra-positive and cd45r-positive.

sperm: cd38-negative igg-negative class switched memory b cell
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a cd38-negative igg-negative memory b cell is a igg-negative class switched memory b cell that lacks igg on the cell surface with the phenotype cd38-negative and igg-negative.
a smooth muscle cell of the uterus.
a monostratified retinal ganglion cell that has post synaptic terminals in sublaminar layer s4 and is depolarized by illumination of its receptive field center.

a cell specialized to detect chemical substances and relay that information centrally in the nervous system. chemoreceptors may monitor external stimuli, as in taste and olfaction, or internal stimuli, such as the concentrations of oxygen and carbon dioxide in the blood.
a fully differentiated plasma cell that secretes igm.
a glandular epithelial cell of the endometrium.
a mono-stratified retinal ganglion cell that has a large dendritic field and a medium dendritic arbor with post synaptic terminals in sublaminar layer s1 and s2.
a dendritic cell that develops from a monocyte.
a memory regulatory t cell with phenotype cd4-positive, cd25-positive, cd127lo, ccr4-positive, and cd45ro-positive.
a pre-b-ii cell is a precursor b cell that expresses immunoglobulin mu heavy chain (ighmu+), and lack expression of cd34, tdt, immunoglobulin kappa light chain and immunoglobulin lambda light chain.
a pyramidal neuron which lacks a tuft formation but extends small radial distances forming a star-like shape.

a stem cell found in the interstitial compartment of the neonatal testis. it is capable of self-renewal as well as differentiation into steroidogenic cells (adult leydig cells). intermediate stages of development include progenitor leydig cells and immature leydig cells.

a keratocyte is a specialized fibroblast residing in the cornea stroma that has a flattened, dendritic cell located between the lamellae with a large flattened nucleus and lengthy processes which communicate with neighboring cells. this corneal layer, representing about 85-90% of corneal thickness, is built up from highly regular collagenous lamellae and extracellular matrix components. keratocytes play the major role in keeping it transparent, healing its wounds, and synthesizing its components. this cell type secretes collagen i, v, vi, and keratin sulfate.
a thymic macrophage found in the thymic medulla.

an excitatory glutamatergic interneuron found in the granular layer of the cerebellar cortex and also in the granule cell domain of the cochlear nucleus. unipolar brush cells have a round or oval cell body with usually a single short dendrite that ends in a brush-like tuft of short dendrites unique to them known as dendrioles.
a lower motor neuron whose soma is located in the anterior horn. anterior horn motor neurons project from the anterior portion of the grey matter in the spinal cord to some skeletal muscles.
a pro-t cell that is lin-negative, cd25-negative, cd127-negative, cd44-positive and kit-positive.

sperm: intestinal crypt stem cell of anorectum
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: an intestinal crypt stem cell that is located in the anorectum.
a sebum secreting cell of the skin that secretes sebum into the hair follicles.

sperm: microfold cell of epithelium of small intestine
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a m cell that is part of the epithelium of small intestine.
a t cell that is located in a vermiform appendix.
a monocyte that expresses cd14 and is negative for the lineage markers cd3, cd19, and cd20.
an intestinal tuft cell that is located in the anorectum.
a long, spindle-shaped supporting cells arranged in parallel rows that secretes components of the tectorial membrane and potassium ions into the endolymph.
the human equivalent of a dn2 thymocyte. typically contains two phases, in the latter of which these thymocytes begin the process of beta selection.
a keratinocyte of the epidermis suprabasal layer. this cell may express the differentiation markers keratin 10 and keratin 1.
a basophilic erythroblast that is glya-positive.
a cell that can perform photosynthesis, in which carbohydrates are synthesized from carbon dioxide and water, using light as the energy source.

an exocrine cell characterized by loss of part of the cytoplasm during the process of secretion. the secreted substance is accumulated at the apical end and is either budded off through the plasma membrane producing secreted vesicles or dissolved in the cytoplasm that is lost during secretion.
a cell that secretes glycosaminoglycans.
an astrocyte of the cerebellum.
a beta motor neuron that innervates the nuclear bag fibers of muscle spindles.

a enteroendocrine cell type that is numerous in ileum, present in jejunum and large intestine, few in duodenum. this cell type produces glucagon-like immunoreactants (glicentin, glucagon-37, glucagon-29, glp-1 and -2) and pyy.

sperm: transitional myocyte of right branch of atrioventricular bundle
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a transitional myocyte that is part of the right branch of atrioventricular bundle.
any basket cell that is part of a cerebellum.

sperm: smooth muscle cell of large intestine
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a smooth muscle cell that is part of the large intestine.
an epithelial cell derived from ectoderm.
a primordial germ cell that is destined to become a male germ cell.

sperm: luminal epithelial cell of mammary gland
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a mammary epithelial cell that occurs in the lumen of the ductal and alveoli structure in the breast.
a renal beta-intercalated cell that is part of the renal connecting tubule.
a cd14-positive monocyte that is also cd16-positive and ccr2-negative.
a progenitor cell of the thrombocyte, a nucleated blood cell involved in coagulation typically seen in birds and other non-mammalian vertebrates.

sperm: basal epithelial cell of tracheobronchial tree
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: an epithelial cell type that lacks the columnar shape typical for other respiratory epithelial cells. this cell type is able to differentiate into other respiratory epithelial cells in response to injury.
a hematopoietic progenitor cell that is capable of developing into only one lineage of hematopoietic cells.

sperm: epithelial cell of proximal tubule segment 1
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: epithelial cell that is part of segment 1 (s1) of the proximal tubule epithelium.
a cd11c-low plasmacytoid dendritic cell that is cd8alpha-positive and cd4-positive.

sperm: b220-positive cd38-positive igg-negative class switched memory b cell
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a b220-positive cd38-positive igg-negative memory b cell is a cd38-positive igg-negative class switched memory b cell that lacks igg on the cell surface with the phenotype b220-positive, cd38-positive, and igg-negative.
a stromal cell of the pancreas.

sperm: cd27-low, cd11b-low immature natural killer cell, mouse
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: an immature natural killer cell that is nk1.1-positive, dx5-positive, ly49-positive, cd27-low and cd11b-low. this cell type is found in high numbers in the liver.

an on-bipolar neuron found in the retina and having connections with cone photoreceptors cells and neurons in the inner half of the inner plexiform layer. the axon terminal is narrowly stratified and are found just below a calretinin-expressing band in sublamina 4 of the inner plexiform layer.
a progenitor cell committed to the erythroid lineage.
a progenitor cell committed to myeloid lineage, including the megakaryocyte and erythroid lineages.
sympathetic noradrenergic neuron.

sperm: transit amplifying cell of small intestine
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a rapidly proliferating population of cells that differentiate from stem cells of the intestinal crypt of the small intestine. stem cells located in the crypts of lieberk hn give rise to proliferating progenitor or transit amplifying cells that differentiate into the four major epithelial cell types. these include columnar absorptive cells or enterocytes, mucous secreting goblet cells, enteroendocrine cells and paneth cells.

a mechanoreceptor located in the acoustic maculae and the semicircular canals that mediates the sense of balance, movement, and head position. the vestibular hair cells are connected to accessory structures in such a way that movements of the head displace their stereocilia. this influences the membrane potential of the cells which relay information about movements via the vestibular part of the vestibulocochlear nerve to the brain stem.
an intestinal enteroendocrine cell that is located in a vermiform appendix.

pioneer neurons establish a pathway in the developing central nervous system and then undergo programmed cell death once the adult axons, which follow them, have made connections with the target site. thus, they are a transient cell type involved in axon guidance.
a horizontal cell with a small cell body, thin dendrites, and small dendritic arbor.

sperm: activated cd4-positive, cd25-positive, ccr4-positive, alpha-beta regulatory t cell, human
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a cd4-positive, cd25-positive, ccr4-positive, alpha-beta t regulatory cell with the phenotype hla-dra-positive, indicating recent activation.

any cell that is located within the interstitium between the cells most prominent in defining a given tissue. "interstitial cell" is a morphological term and refers to a variety of cells with differing origins and phenotypes.

sperm: cd34-positive, cd38-positive megakaryocyte erythroid progenitor cell
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a megakaryocyte erythroid progenitor cell is cd34-positive, cd38-positive and is il3-receptor alpha-negative and cd45ra-negative.
a thymocyte that has the phenotype cd4-negative, cd8-negative, cd44-negative, and cd25-positive and expressing the t cell receptor beta-chain in complex with the pre-t cell receptor alpha chain.
an epithelial cell that is part of the glomerular capsule.
a supporting cell of the vestibular epithelium.

an adult endothelial progenitor cell that is resident of adult vasculature and capable of differentiating to regenerate endothelial cell populations. endothelial colony forming cells are characterised in vivo by clonal proliferative status, de novo vessel formation, homing to ischemic sites and paracrine support of angiogenesis. these cells are phenotypically similar to endothelial cells.
a cell that is part of the choroid plexus.
a neuron of the substantia nigra.
a retinal ganglion with cell medium cell bodies and medium to large dendritic fields.

one of the two photoreceptor cell types in the vertebrate retina. in cones the photopigment is in invaginations of the cell membrane of the outer segment. cones are less sensitive to light than rods, but they provide vision with higher spatial and temporal acuity, and the combination of signals from cones with different pigments allows color vision.
a paneth cell of the appendix.
a specialized epithelial cell that contains "feet" that interdigitate with the "feet" of other glomerular epithelial cells in the mesonephros.
cd4-positive, alpha-beta t cell that produces il-22.
a receptor in the vascular system, particularly the aorta and carotid sinus, which is sensitive to stretch of the vessel walls.

sperm: anterior lateral line neuromast supporting cell
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: any neuromast support cell that is part of a anterior lateral line.

sperm: smooth muscle cell of the internal thoracic artery
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a smooth muscle of the internal thoracic artery.
a skeletal muscle cell that is part of the tongue.
a b cell that is mature, having left the bone marrow. initially, these cells are igm-positive and igd-positive, and they can be activated by antigen.
a goblet cell that is part of the epithelium of pancreatic duct.
a photoreceptor cell that is sensitive to red light.
an unswitched memory b cell is a memory b cell that has the phenotype igm-positive, igd-positive, cd27-positive, cd138-negative, igg-negative, ige-negative, and iga-negative.

sperm: medulla-projecting glutamatergic neuron of the primary motor cortex
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: an extratelencephalic-projecting glutamatergic neuron located in layer 5b of the primary motor cortex that projects to the medulla. my et cells are large, big-tufted cells with the apical dendrite often bifurcating close to the soma, suggesting they are corticospinal cells. my et cells have bigger hyperpolarization sag, lower input resistance, and smaller ap width, compared to l5 it neurons.
an epithelial cell that lines the peripheral gas exchange region of the lungs of air-breathing vertebrates.

sperm: smooth muscle cell neural crest derived
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a smooth muscle cell derived from the neural crest.

sperm: smooth muscle fiber of ascending colon
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a smooth muscle cell that is part of the ascending colon.
an interneuron that is derived from the caudal ganglionic eminence.
a bipolar neuron found in the retina and having connections with photoreceptors cells and neurons in the inner plexiform layer.
an epithelial cell of thyroid gland.
an amacrine cell that uses glycine as a neurotransmitter.
a neuron that has dendritic processes radiating from the cell body forming a star-like shape.
an endothelial stalk cell is a specialized endothelial cell that follows behind the tip cell of an angiogenic sprout.
an amacrine cell with a small dendritic field with post-synaptic terminals in s3 and s4.
a nk1.1-positive t cell that is ly49h-negative.
a tissue-resident macrophage found in a secondary lymphoid organ.

sperm: enterocyte of epithelium proper of ileum
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: an enterocyte that is part of the epithelium proper of ileum.
a fibroblast of the periodontium.
a columnar cell of the colon that is part of the colonic epithelium.
a giant cell 50 to 100 micron in diameter, with a greatly lobulated nucleus, found in the bone marrow. mature blood platelets are released from its cytoplasm.
an acidophilic cell of the anterior pituitary that produces prolactin.
any microvascular endothelial cell that is part of a female urethra.
any fibroblast that is part of a spleen.
skeletogenic cell that secretes dentine matrix, is derived from the odontogenic papilla, and develops from a preodontoblast cell.

sperm: effector memory cd4-positive, alpha-beta t cell
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: cd4-positive, alpha-beta memory t cell with the phenotype ccr7-negative, cd127-positive, cd45ra-negative, cd45ro-positive, and cd25-negative.

a cell type found in the gastrointestinal and respiratory tracts that is characterized by the presence of a tuft of blunt, squat microvilli (120-140 per cell). function of this cell type is not known.
a dermal dendritic cell that is langerin-positive and cd103-positive.
a cd8-positive, alpha-beta t cell that has the phenotype cxcr3-negative, ccr6-positive, ccr5-high, cd45ra-negative, and capable of producing il-17 and some ifng.
a neuron that is part of the somatic sensory system. somatosensory neurons innervate the skin or integument to detect different types of thermal, chemical, and mechanical touch stimuli.

a cell that is commited to differentiating into a muscle cell. embryonic myoblasts develop from the mesoderm. they undergo proliferation, migrate to their various sites, and then differentiate into the appropriate form of myocytes. myoblasts also occur as transient populations of cells in muscles undergoing repair.

sperm: nucleus pulposus cell of intervertebral disc
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a connective tissue cell of the nucleus pulposus cell of intervertebral disc.

a cell that transports hormones from neurosecretory cells. this nerve cell is characterized by bipolar shape and endfeet that contact a basal lamina around blood vessels, and/or the pia mater or vitreous body of the eye and additionally contact the ventricular surface or sub-retinal space.
an interneuron that is derived from the medial ganglionic eminence.
a retinal ganglion cell c inner that has sparse dendritic density, and large dendritic field.
a reticulocyte that is glya-positive.

sperm: smooth muscle cell of large intestine smooth muscle longitudinal layer
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a(n) smooth muscle cell that is part of a(n) large intestine smooth muscle longitudinal layer.
muscle precursor cell that is adjacent to the notochord and part of the presomitic mesoderm.
a pre-bcr-positive precursor b cell that is cd24-high, cd25-positive, cd43-positive, cd45r-positive and bp-positive.

sperm: cd27-low, cd11b-high natural killer cell, mouse
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a cd27-low, cd11b-high natural killer cell that has a higher threshold of activation due to higher expression of inhibitory receptors.
cd4-positive alpha-beta t cell with the phenotype cd25-positive, ctla-4-positive, and foxp3-positive with regulatory function.
a cell found in the bone marrow. this can include fibroblasts, macrophages, adipocytes, osteoblasts, osteoclasts, endothelial cells and hematopoietic cells.
a conventional dendritic cell that is cd103-positive. this cell type is usually found in non-lymphoid tissue.

a thymocyte that has a t cell receptor consisting of a gamma chain containing vgamma2 segment, and a delta chain. this cell type is cd4-negative, cd8-negative and cd24-negative. this cell-type is found in the fetal thymus.
a cd8-positive, alpha-beta t cell that has differentiated into a memory t cell.
a fully differentiated plasma cell that secretes igg.
a cell type that varies from squamous to columnar, depending on their activity with microvillus directed luminally. this cell produces and secretes thyroid hormones.
a neuron that releases serotonin as a neurotransmitter.
a goblet cell that is part of the epithelium proper of duodenum.
an oblong or round asexual spore formed from conidial chains.
an extracellular matrix secreting cell that secretes eggshell.
a hematopoietic multipotent progenitor cell that is cd34-positive, cd38-negative, cd45ra-negative, and cd90-negative.
a glandular epithelial cell that is part of the stomach.
an endothelial cell that is part of the venule.
an enucleate erythrocyte that is glya-positive.
a central nervous system macrophage found at the interface between the blood and the cerebrospinal fluid in the brain. this cell expresses scavenger receptors.

a cell of hematopoietic origin, typically resident in particular tissues, specialized in the uptake, processing, and transport of antigens to lymph nodes for the purpose of stimulating an immune response via t cell activation. these cells are lineage negative (cd3-negative, cd19-negative, cd34-negative, and cd56-negative).
a paracrine cell is a secretory cell that secretes an agonist into intercellular spaces in which it diffuses to a target cell other than that which produced it.

an erythroid progenitor cell is kit-positive, ly6a-negative, cd41-negative, cd127-negative, and cd123-negative. this cell type is also described as being lin-negative, kit-positive, cd150-negative, cd41-negative, cd105-positive, and fcgr-negative.

an epithelial cell found in the basal part of the intestinal glands (crypts of lieberkuhn) including the appendix. paneth cells synthesize and secrete lysozyme and cryptdins. numerous in the deeper parts of the intestinal crypts, particularly in the duodenum, rich in zinc, contain large acidophilic granules, with irregular apical microvilli and prominent membrane-bound vacuoles containing matrix.
a specialized cell involved in auditory sensory perception.
a neurecto-epithelial cell found in the arachnoid villi of dura mater. this cell type facilitates flow of cerebrospinal fluid into the blood.
scattered in duodenojejunal mucosa, this enteroendocrine cell secretes secretin and serotonin.
an epithelial fate stem cell derived form the amnion membrane.
cd7-positive lymphoid progenitor cell is a lymphoid progenitor cell that is cd34-positive, cd7-positive and is cd45ra-negative.
an endocrine cell that is located in the epithelium of the gastrointestinal tract or in the pancreas.
an amacrine cell with a medium dendritic field and post-synaptic terminals that stratify at s2, with a second stratification that occurs in s3 and s4.
any cell in the retina, the innermost layer or coating at the back of the eyeball, which is sensitive to light and in which the optic nerve terminates.
a mature gamma-delta t cell located in the epidermis that regulates wound healing.

sperm: b220-positive cd38-negative unswitched memory b cell
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a b220-positive cd38-negative unswitched memory b cell is a cd38-negative unswitched memory b cell that has the phenotype b220-positive, cd38-negative, igd-positive, cd138-negative, and igg-negative.
a transitional myocyte that is part of the atrioventricular bundle.

a germinal center b cell that is rapidly dividing and has the phenotype igd-negative, cd38-positive, and cd77-positive. somatic hypermutation of the immunoglobulin v gene region can occur during proliferation of this cell type.
a renal alpha-intercalated cell that is part of the collecting duct of the renal tubule.
a neoplastic cell that is capable of entering a surrounding tissue

sperm: paneth cell of epithelium proper of small intestine
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a paneth cell that is part of the epithelium proper of small intestine.
a melanocyte of the retina. this cell type is distinct from pigmented retinal epithelium.

a mechanoreceptor cell of the auditory or vestibular system that is sensitive to auditory stimuli. the accessory sensory structures are arranged so that appropriate stimuli cause movement of the hair-like projections (stereocilia and kinocilia) which relay the information centrally in the nervous system.
a cell capable of processing and presenting lipid and protein antigens to t cells in order to initiate an immune response.

a endothelial cell of a lymphatic vessel. the border of the oak leaf-shaped endothelial cell of initial lymphatics are joined by specialized buttons. the discontinuous feature of buttons distinguishes them from zippers in collecting lymphatics, but both types of junctions are composed of proteins typical of adherens junctions and tight junctions found in the endothelium of blood vessels. buttons seal the sides of flaps of the oak leaf-shaped endothelial cell, leaving open the tips of flaps as routes for fluid entry without disassembly and reformation of intercellular junctions.

a basophil precursor in the granulocytic series, being a cell intermediate in development between a promyelocyte and a metamyelocyte. in this stage, production of primary granules is complete and basophil-specific granules has started. no nucleolus is present. markers are being integrin alpha-m-positive, fucosyltransferase fut4-positive, cd33-positive, cd24-positive, aminopeptidase n-positive.
a hematopoeitic stem cell found in the blood. normally found in very limited numbers in the peripheral circulation (less than 0.1% of all nucleated cells).

sperm: lymphatic endothelial cell of subcapsular sinus floor
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a lymphatic endothelial cell located in the subcapsular sinus floor of a lymph node. in human, it's characterized by a unique marker expression (tnfrsf9+).
a smooth muscle cell that is part of the duodenum.
an epithelial cell of the prostate.
a cd4-positive, cd8-negative thymocyte that is cd24-positive and expresses high levels of the alpha-beta t cell receptor.
any neuron having a sensory function. an afferent neuron conveying sensory impulses.
a cell of the seminiferous tubule epithelium.

an adult angioblastic cell released from the bone marrow, or from the kidney in some teleost species, capable of blood circulation and participation in angiogenesis by differentiating into blood vessel endothelial cells.

epithelial progenitor cell of the lung. club cells are dome-shaped with short microvilli but no cilia. they function to protect the bronchiolar epithelium. club cells also multiply and differentiate into ciliated cells to regenerate the bronchiolar epithelium.

sperm: dx5-negative, nk1.1-positive immature natural killer cell, mouse
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: an immature natural killer cell that is nk1.1-positive and dx-5 negative.
any microvascular endothelial cell that is part of a adipose tissue.
a lymphocyte of b lineage that has gotten larger after being stimulated by an antigen.
glandular cell of appendix epithelium. example: goblet cells. enterocytes or absorptive cells. enteroendocrine and m cells.
a smooth muscle cell that is part of any lymphatic vessel.
a cell that is part of a tip of a renal papilla.

sperm: cd8-alpha alpha positive, gamma-delta intraepithelial t cell
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a gamma-delta intraepithelial t cell that has the phenotype cd8-alpha alpha-positive.

sperm: cardiac pacemaker cell of sinoatrial node
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a nodal myocyte that is part of the sinoatrial node.
an excitatory neuron that has its soma located in the thalamic complex.
fat cells with light coloration and few mitochondria. they contain a scant ring of cytoplasm surrounding a single large lipid droplet or vacuole.

an off-bipolar neuron found in the retina and having connections with cone photoreceptors cells and neurons in the outer half of the inner plexiform layer. the cell has a diffuse axon terminal with varicosities in sublaminae 1 and 2 of the inner plexiform layer.
a cell that initiates an electrical signal and passes that signal to another cell.

a neutrophil precursor in the granulocytic series, being a cell intermediate in development between a promyelocyte and a metamyelocyte. in this stage, production of primary granules is complete and neutrophil-specific granules has started. no nucleolus is present. this cell type is cd13-positive, cd16-negative, integrin alpha-m-positive, cd15-positive, cd33-positive, cd24-positive, c/ebp-a-positive, c/ebpe-positive, pu.1-positive, lactotransferrin-positive, myeloperoxidase-positive and ngal-positive.

a pre-b cell that is pre-bcr-negative, and the kappa- and lambda- light immunoglobulin light chain-negative, cd43-low, and is bp-1-positive, cd45r-positive and cd25-positive. this cell type is also described as being aa4-positive, igm-negative, cd19-positive, cd43-low/negative, and hsa-positive.
a b cell that is cd19-positive.
a bistratified retinal ganglion cell that has a dendrite field that terminates in sublaminar layer s2 and a second dendrite field that terminates in sublaminar layer s4.

sperm: endothelial cell of pericentral hepatic sinusoid
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: an endothelial cell found in the centrilobular region hepatic sinusoid, near the central vein. the fenestrae of these cells are smaller but more numerous compared with those of endothelial cells near the periportal region of the hepatic sinusoid.

sperm: spinal cord medial motor column neuron
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: any neuron that is part of a spinal cord medial motor column.
a type d cell found in the stomach.
a splenic macrophage found in the white pulp of the spleen. markers include f4/80-negative, cd68-positive, and macrosialin-positive.
a somatic epithelial cell of the insect egg chamber.

sperm: cd4-negative, cd8-negative type i nk t cell secreting interleukin-4
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a mature nk t cell that secretes interleukin-4 and enhances th2 immune responses.

any cell that is part of the esophageal non-keratinized stratified squamous epithelium. in humans, the esophagus, which requires flexibility to accommodate swallowing of a bolus, is covered with a non-keratinized epithelium.

sperm: inverted l6 intratelencephalic projecting glutamatergic neuron of the primary motor cortex (mmus)
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: a l6 intratelencephalic projecting glutamatergic neuron of the primary motor cortex that has inverted pyramidal morphology.

a connective tissue cell which secretes an extracellular matrix rich in collagen and other macromolecules. flattened and irregular in outline with branching processes. appear fusiform or spindle-shaped.

a type ii muscle cell that contains a low content of myoglobin, relatively few mitochondria, relatively few blood capillaries and large amounts of glycogen. type ii b fibres are white, geared to generate atp by anaerobic metabolic processes, not able to supply skeletal muscle fibres continuously with sufficient atp, fatigue easily, split atp at a fast rate and have a fast contraction velocity.

sperm: intestinal crypt stem cell of appendix
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: an intestinal crypt stem cell that is located in the vermiform appendix. these stem cells reside at the bottom of crypts in the appendix and are highly proliferative. they either differentiate into transit amplifying cells or self-renew to form new stem cells.
a mature nk cell that is nk1.1-positive.

a type of monocyte characterized by low expression of ccr2, low responsiveness to monocyte chemoattractant ccl2/mcp1, low phagocytic activity, and decrease size relative to classical monocytes, but increased co-stimulatory activity. may also play a role in tissue repair.
a glial cell that ensheathes axons of neuron in the peripheral nervous system and are necessary for their maintainance and function.

an immature b cell is a b cell that has the phenotype surface igm-positive and surface igd-negative, and have not undergone class immunoglobulin class switching or peripheral encounter with antigen and activation.

a follicular b cell that is igd-positive, cd23-negative, and cd38-negative. this naive cell type is activated in the extrafollicular areas through interaction with interdigitating dendritic cells and antigen-specific cd4-positive t cells.

sperm: non-medulla, extratelencephalic-projecting glutamatergic neuron of the primary motor cortex
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: an extratelencephalic-projecting glutamatergic neuron located in layer 5b of the primary motor cortex that does not project to the medulla. non-my et cells are large, big-tufted cells with the apical dendrite often bifurcating close to the soma, suggesting they are corticospinal cells. non-my et cells have bigger hyperpolarization sag, lower input resistance, and smaller ap width, compared to l5 it neurons.
a cell of the middle germ layer of the embryo.
an epithelial cell that is part of the appendix.
a mature alpha-beta t cell that expresses an alpha-beta t cell receptor and the cd4 coreceptor.

sperm: epithelial cell of stratum spinosum of esophageal epithelium
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: an epithelial cell of stratum spinosum of esophageal epithelium.

a type i pneumocyte is a flattened, branched pneumocyte that covers more than 98% of the alveolar surface. this large cell has thin (50-100 nm) cytoplasmic extensions to form the air-blood barrier essential for normal gas exchange.
a hematopoietic oligopotent progenitor cell that has the ability to differentiate into limited cell types but lacks lineage cell markers and self renewal capabilities.

the most primitive precursor in the granulocytic series, having fine, evenly distributed chromatin, several nucleoli, a high nuclear-to-cytoplasmic ration (5:1-7:1), and a nongranular basophilic cytoplasm. they reside in the bone marrow.
a dn2 thymocyte that is kit-hi.
an epithelial cell found in the trachea.

an absorptive cell of the gut epithelium that endocytoses microorganisms and intact macromolecules from the gut lumen and transports them to the subepithelial space where they are presented to antigen-presenting cells and lymphocytes.
an epithelial cell of the anal column.

a stem cell that can give rise to the cells of the liver. the term usually refers to the self-renewing pool of hepatocyte precursors in the adult liver (differently from 'hepatoblast', often used for fetal precursors of hepatocytes).
conventional dendritic cell is a dendritic cell that is cd11c-high.
the motor neurons of vertebrates that directly innervate skeletal muscles. they receive input from upper motor neurons.
an innate lymphoid cell in the human with the phenotype nkp46-positive that is a precusor for nk cells and ilc3 cells.
an innate lyphoid cell with an immature phenotype.
a long lived plasma cell that secretes ige.

sperm: acidophil cell of pars distalis of adenohypophysis
a mature male germ cell that develops fr: an acidophilic chromophil cell that of the anterior pituitary gland.
cd4-positive alpha-beta t cell with regulatory function that produces il-10.

a cell capable of producting norepiniphrine. norepiniphrine is a catecholamine with multiple roles including as a hormone and a neurotransmitter. in addition, epiniphrine is synthesized from norepiniphrine by the actions of the phenylethanolamine n-methyltransferase enzyme.
